sor|[[2016 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 4 \u00d7 50 metre mixed medley relay|4\u00d750 m mixed medley]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2014 Doha|[[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 4 \u00d7 50 metre mixed freestyle relay|4\u00d750 m mixed freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2018 Hangzhou]]|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 50 metre freestyle|50 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Pan American Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 Pan American Games|2015 Toronto]] | [[Swimming at the 2015 Pan American Games|100 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2019 Pan American Games|2019 Lima]] | [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games|50 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2015 Toronto|[[Swimming at the 2015 Pan American Games|50 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2019 Pan American Games|2019 Lima]] | [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games|4\u00d7100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games|2019 Lima]] | [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games - Mixed 4 x 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100 m mixed freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2015 Toronto| [[Swimming at the 2015 Pan American Games|4\u00d7100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2015 Toronto|[[Swimming at the 2015 Pan American Games|4\u00d7100 m medley]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games|2019 Lima]] | [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|100 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2019 Pan American Games|2019 Lima]] | [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m medley]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[South American Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 South American Games|2014 Santiago]] |[[Swimming at the 2014 South American Games|4\u00d7100 m medley]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2014 Santiago |[[Swimming at the 2014 South American Games|100 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2014 Santiago |[[Swimming at the 2014 South American Games|100 m butterfly]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FINA World Junior Swimming Championships|World Junior Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2008 FINA Youth World Swimming Championships|2008 Monterrey]] |[[2008 FINA Youth World Swimming Championships|50 m backstroke]]}}\n}}\n{{Portuguese name|Pires|de Medeiros}}\n'''Etiene Pires de Medeiros''' (born 24 May 1991) is a Brazilian competitive [[Swimming (sport)|swimmer]] who participates in backstroke and freestyle events.<ref>{{cite web|title = UOL profile|work = UOL|year = 2011|url = http://pan.uol.com.br/2011/atletas-brasileiros/etiene-medeiros/index.htm|archive-url = https://archive.today/20130424084129/http://pan.uol.com.br/2011/atletas-brasileiros/etiene-medeiros/index.htm|url-status = dead|archive-date = 24 April 2013|accessdate = 17 April 2013|language = pt}}</ref> Widely regarded as the best Brazilian woman swimmer of all time, Medeiros was the first Brazilian to win an individual gold medal in a [[FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|World Championship]] (long and short course) and [[Pan American Games]], and the first to be a world record-holder in the modern era (only [[Maria Lenk]] in 1939 had accomplished this feat)\n\n==International career==\n===2008\u201312===\nAt 17 years old, Etiene Medeiros won the silver medal in the 50-metre backstroke at the [[2008 FINA Youth World Swimming Championships]] in [[Monterrey]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Closing with the female swimming in high | work = CBDA | date = 21 November 2010 | url = http://www.cbda.org.br/noticias/encerramento-com-a-natacao-feminina-em-alta|accessdate = 17 April 2013|language=pt}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2009 World Aquatics Championships]] in [[Rome]], she finished 21st in the 50-metre backstroke.<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 50-metre backstroke at 2009 Rome | work = OmegaTiming | date = 29 July 2009 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=0001090B002A000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01|accessdate = 17 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nMedeiros was at the [[2010 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)]] in [[Dubai]], where she finished 17th in the 50-metre backstroke <ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 50-metre backstroke at 2010 Dubai | work = OmegaTiming | date = 18 December 2010 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010A000040000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01|accessdate = 17 April 2013}}</ref> and 30th in the 100-metre backstroke.<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 100-metre backstroke at 2010 Dubai | work = OmegaTiming | date = 15 December 2010 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010A000005000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 | accessdate = 17 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nShe joined the national delegation which attended the [[2011 World Aquatics Championships]] in [[Shanghai]], [[China]], winning the vacancy after the positive doping of [[Fabiola Molina]]. Etiene finished 43rd in the 100-metre backstroke, with a time of 1:05.18.<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 100-metre backstroke at the 2011 Shanghai | work = OmegaTiming | date = 25 July 2011 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010B0D0012000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01| accessdate = 17 April 2013}}</ref> She also swam the 50-metre backstroke, where she finished 25th<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 50-metre backstroke at the 2011 Shanghai | work = OmegaTiming | date = 27 July 2011 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010B0D002D000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01| accessdate = 17 April 2013}}</ref> and in the 4\u00d7100-metre medley, where she finished 17th.<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 4\u00d7100-metre medley at 2011 Shanghai | work = OmegaTiming | date = 30 July 2011 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010B0D0059000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 | accessdate = 17 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2011 Pan American Games]], Etiene finished 10th in the 100-metre backstroke heats, and did not go to the final.<ref>{{cite web | title = Fabiola Molina wins the 100-metre backstroke and go to the final | work = Lancenet | date = 16 October 2011 | url = http://www.lancenet.com.br/minuto/Fabiola-Molina-vence-eliminatoria-costas_0_573542677.html | accessdate = 17 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nShe was at the [[2012 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)]] in [[Istanbul]], where she finished 10th in the 50-metre backstroke <ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 50-metre backstroke at 2012 Istanbul | work = OmegaTiming | date = 15 December 2012 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010C010D01011A01FFFFFFFFFFFF02|accessdate = 17 April 2013}}</ref> and 28th in the 100-metre backstroke.<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 100-metre backstroke at 2012 Istanbul | work = OmegaTiming | date = 12 December 2012 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010C010D01011B00FFFFFFFFFFFF02 | accessdate = 17 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2013\u201316===\nIn January 2013, she moved to S\u00e3o Paulo and start work with Coach Fernando Vanzella in club SESI-SP.\nIn April 2013, she won the Maria Lenk Trophy in Brazil, with a time of 27.88 seconds in the 50-metre backstroke, best mark of her life, and one of the best times of the year in the proof.<ref>{{cite web | title = Maria Lenk Trophy 2013: Jo\u00e3o is the best of 2013 | work = CBDA | date = 27 April 2013 | url = http://www.cbda.org.br/noticias/trofeu-maria-lenk-2013-joao-e-o-melhor-de-2013 | accessdate = 31 July 2013 | language = pt | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130702163851/http://www.cbda.org.br/noticias/trofeu-maria-lenk-2013-joao-e-o-melhor-de-2013 | archive-date = 2 July 2013 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Kazan 2015 - Etiene Medeiros.jpg|thumbnail|200px|Medeiros in Kazan 2015]]\n\nAt the [[2013 World Aquatics Championships]] in [[Barcelona]], she finished 21st in the [[Swimming at the 2013 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|100-metre backstroke]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Ahead of Lochte, Nicolas Oliveira goes to semis after 6 months out of the pool | publisher = SPORTV | date = 29 July 2013 | url = http://sportv.globo.com/site/eventos/mundial-de-esportes-aquaticos/noticia/2013/07/frente-de-lochte-nicolas-oliveira-vai-semis-apos-6-meses-fora-da-piscina.html| accessdate = 29 July 2013|language=pt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 100-metre backstroke at 2013 Barcelona | work = OmegaTiming | date = 29 July 2013 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010D020101011B00FFFFFFFFFFFF02|accessdate = 29 July 2013}}</ref> In the [[Swimming at the 2013 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|50-metre backstroke]], qualified for the final with the fifth fastest time, 27.89 seconds, one hundredth of her personal best.<ref>{{cite web | title = Etiene Medeiros goes to the 50-metre backstroke final with 5th best time | work = UOL | date = 31 July 2013 | url = http://esporte.uol.com.br/ultimas-noticias/afp/2013/07/31/etiene-medeiros-vai-a-final-dos-50m-costas-com-5-melhor-tempo.htm| accessdate = 31 July 2013|language=pt}}</ref> In the final, she finished in 4th place, with a time of 27.83 seconds, her personal best, getting the best placement of a Brazilian woman in the World Championships.<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 50-metre backstroke at 2013 Barcelona | work = OmegaTiming | date = 1 August 2013 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010D020101011A02FFFFFFFFFFFF02|accessdate = 1 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Glasses break, but Etienne reaches historic fourth place in Barcelona| publisher = SPORTV | date = 1 August 2013 | url = http://sportv.globo.com/site/eventos/mundial-de-esportes-aquaticos/noticia/2013/08/oculos-quebra-mas-etiene-consegue-quarto-lugar-historico-em-barcelona.html|accessdate = 1 August 2013|language=pt}}</ref> She also finished 12th in the [[Swimming at the 2013 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100-metre medley]], along with [[Daynara de Paula]], [[Larissa Oliveira]] and [[Beatriz Travalon]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 4\u00d7100-metre medley at 2013 Barcelona | work = OmegaTiming | date = 4 August 2013 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010D020101043900FFFFFFFFFFFF02|accessdate = 4 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2014 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships]] in [[Gold Coast, Queensland]], she finished 5th in the 4x100-metre freestyle relay, along with Graciele Herrmann, Daynara de Paula and Alessandra Marchioro; 5th in the 4x100-metre medley relay, along with Graciele Herrmann, Ana Carla Carvalho and Daynara de Paula; 6th in the 50-metre freestyle; 7th in the 100-metre butterfly; and 11th in the 100-metre backstroke.<ref>{{cite web | title = Fratus won gold in the 50m freestyle with the Pan-Pacific record | work = CBDA | date = 24 August 2014 | url = http://www.cbda.org.br/noticias/fratus-e-ouro-nos-50m-livre-com-recorde-do-pan-pacifico|accessdate =20 September 2014|language=pt}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 September 2014, participating in the [[Jos\u00e9 Finkel Trophy]] (short course competition) in [[Guaratinguet\u00e1]], Medeiros broke three South American records: in the 50-metre freestyle with a time of 24.15, in the 50-metre backstroke with a time of 26.41, and in the 100-metre backstroke with a time of 57.53.<ref>{{cite web | title = Miguel Valente does best time in the world in the year and Etiene hits her fourth South American record | work = CBDA | date = 4 September 2014 | url = http://www.cbda.org.br/noticias/miguel-valente-faz-melhor-tempo-do-mundo-no-ano-e-etiene-bateu-seu-quarto-recorde-sul-americano | accessdate = 20 September 2014|language=pt}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 December 2014, participating in the [[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)]] in Doha, Qatar, Medeiros broke the world record in the 50-metre backstroke with a time of 25.67.<ref>{{cite web | title = BRAZIL\u2019S ETIENE MEDEIROS BREAKS 50 BACKSTROKE WORLD RECORD IN DOHA | work = swimswam| date = 7 December 2014 | url = http://swimswam.com/brazils-etiene-medeiros-breaks-50-backstroke-world-record-doha/ | accessdate = 7 December 2014 }}</ref> Medeiros was the first woman in Brazil to get an individual medal in World Championships, and the first to win a gold medal. Medeiros won 3 medals in the competition: the gold in the [[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|Women's 50 metre backstroke]], another gold in the [[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 4 \u00d7 50 metre mixed medley relay|4 \u00d7 50 metre mixed medley relay]] (along with Felipe Fran\u00e7a, Nicholas Santos and Larissa Oliveira), and a bronze medal in the [[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 4 \u00d7 50 metre mixed freestyle relay|4 \u00d7 50 metre mixed freestyle relay]] (along with Cesar Cielo, Jo\u00e3o de Lucca and Larissa Oliveira). On 3 December, in the 4 \u00d7 50 metre mixed medley relay, Medeiros opened the final with a time of 25.83, and Brazil won the race beating the South American record with a time of 1:37.26, only 0.09 seconds from beating USA's world record (1:37.17). On 6 December, in the 4 \u00d7 50 metre mixed freestyle relay, Brazil broke the South American record with a time of 1:29.17, only 4 hundredths slower than Russia, which won the silver medal. In the 50-metre backstroke, Medeiros broke the Americas record in the semifinal with a time of 25.99, and the World record in the final with a time of 25.67. Medeiros also broke 2 times the South American record in the  [[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|100 metre backstroke]], with a time of 57.36 at heats and 57.13 in the semifinals, finishing in 7th place in the final; and 2 times in [[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 50 metre medley relay|Women's 4 \u00d7 50 metre medley relay]], with a time of 1:47.20 at heats and 1:46.47 in the final, finishing in 5th place.<ref>{{cite web | title = Doha gives to Brazil the short pool crown | work = CBDA | date = 7 December 2014 | url = http://www.cbda.org.br/noticias/doha-da-ao-brasil-a-coroa-em-piscina-curta |accessdate = 12 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Full Results at 2014 Doha | work = OmegaTiming | date = 8 December 2014 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010E010DFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF05 |accessdate = 12 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt the Brazilian Open, in [[Rio de Janeiro]], she broke the Americas record in the 50-metre backstroke,  with a time of 27.37.<ref>{{cite web | title = Pinheros takes the leadership at the Brazilian Open | work = CBDA | date = 19 December 2014 | url = http://www.cbda.org.br/noticias/pinheiros-assume-a-lideranca-do-brasileiro-senior-e-do-open | accessdate = 19 December 2014|language=pt}}</ref> She also broke the South American record in the 50-metre freestyle, with a time of 24.74.<ref>{{cite web | title = Victorious end of year to the Brazilian Swimming | work = CBDA | date = 20 December 2014 | url = http://www.cbda.org.br/noticias/fim-de-ano-vitorioso-para-a-natacao-brasileira | accessdate = 20 December 2014|language=pt}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ouro e prata nos 100m nado costas. (22016177812).jpg|thumbnail|250px|[[Natalia de Luccas]] (left) and Etiene Medeiros, 2015]]\n\nAt the [[Swimming at the 2015 Pan American Games|2015 Pan American Games]] in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada, Medeiros made history again, winning the first gold medal in the history of Brazilian women's swimming at Pan American Games. In the [[Swimming at the 2015 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|Women's 100 metre backstroke]], she did a time of 59.61, a new Pan Am Games and South American record. An hour after the unprecedented gold, she won the silver medal in the [[Swimming at the 2015 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's 50 metre freestyle|Women's 50 metre freestyle]], with a new South American record, 24.55.<ref>{{cite web|title = Etiene Medeiros is the first Brazilian woman swimming champion at Pan American Games|work=ClicRBS|date = 18 July 2015|url = http://wp.clicrbs.com.br/brasilolimpico/2015/07/18/etiene-medeiros-e-a-primeira-nadadora-brasileira-campea-pan-americana/?topo=52,1,1,,171,e171|accessdate = 19 July 2015|language=pt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Historic day for Brazil women's swimming in the Pan|work = Best Swimming|date = 18 July 2015|url = http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/07/18/dia-historico-para-a-natacao-feminina-do-brasil-no-pan/|accessdate = 19 July 2015|language = pt|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150923184228/http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/07/18/dia-historico-para-a-natacao-feminina-do-brasil-no-pan/|archive-date = 23 September 2015|url-status = dead}}</ref> In this competition, she also helped the Brazilian team to win two bronze medals in the [[Swimming at the 2015 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay]] (this, breaking the South American record, with a time of 3:37.39)<ref>{{cite web|title = Brazil is gold in the 4x100m freestyle and Thiago Pereira opens count towards record|work=Globoesporte|date = 14 July 2015|url = http://globoesporte.globo.com/jogos-pan-americanos/noticia/2015/07/brasil-confirma-favoritismo-vence-revezamento-4x100m-e-fatura-o-ouro.html|accessdate = 19 July 2015|language=pt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = First day of five medals, and two gold medals to Brazil, but the party was Canadian|work = Best Swimming|date = 15 July 2015|url = http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/07/15/primeiro-dia-de-5-medalhas-e-2-ouros-para-o-brasil-mas-a-festa-foi-canadense/|accessdate = 19 July 2015|language = pt|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150721172457/http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/07/15/primeiro-dia-de-5-medalhas-e-2-ouros-para-o-brasil-mas-a-festa-foi-canadense/|archive-date = 21 July 2015|url-status = dead}}</ref> and [[Swimming at the 2015 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay]].<ref>{{cite web|title = Without Thiago Pereira, Brazilian relay closes swimming with gold|work=O Estado de S.Paulo|date = 18 July 2015|url = http://esportes.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,sem-thiago--revezamento-brasileiro-tem-grande-atuacao-e-fecha-natacao-com-ouro,1727975|accessdate = 19 July 2015|language=pt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = How it was the last day of the Pan in Toronto|work = Best Swimming|date = 19 July 2015|url = http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/07/19/como-foi-o-ultimo-dia-de-prova-do-pan-em-toronto/|accessdate = 19 July 2015|language = pt|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150721172503/http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/07/19/como-foi-o-ultimo-dia-de-prova-do-pan-em-toronto/|archive-date = 21 July 2015|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[Swimming at the 2015 World Aquatics Championships|2015 World Aquatics Championships]] in [[Kazan]], in the [[Swimming at the 2015 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|Women's 50 metre backstroke]], Etiene broke another paradigm by becoming the first Brazilian woman to climb the podium in a long-course World Championships. She won the silver medal, beating the Americas record with a time of 27.26.<ref>{{cite web | title = Silver in the 50m backstroke, Etiene is 1st in Brazil to rise to the podium of the World | work = Globoesporte | date = 6 August 2015 | url = http://globoesporte.globo.com/natacao/noticia/2015/08/prata-nos-50m-costas-etiene-e-1-do-brasil-subir-ao-podio-do-mundial.html|accessdate = 6 August 2015|language=pt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 50-metre backstroke at 2015 Kazan | work = OmegaTiming | date = 6 August 2015 | url = http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010F020001011A02FFFFFFFFFFFF02|accessdate = 6 August 2015}}</ref> In the [[Swimming at the 2015 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|Women's 100 metre backstroke]], she came close to go to the final, finishing in 9th place, with a time of 59.97.<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 100-metre backstroke at 2015 Kazan | work = OmegaTiming | date = 3 August 2015 | url = http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010F020001011B01FFFFFFFFFFFF02 | accessdate = 3 August 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170803163454/http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010F020001011B01FFFFFFFFFFFF02 | archive-date = 3 August 2017 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Gold in Pan, Etiene stays in ninth place and doesn't go to the 100m backstroke final at the World Championships|publisher=ESPN|date = 3 August 2015|url = http://espn.uol.com.br/noticia/532973_ouro-no-pan-etiene-fica-em-nono-e-nao-vai-a-final-dos-100m-costas-no-mundial|accessdate = 3 August 2015|language=pt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Brazil wins silver with Nicholas Santos, in an evening with 2 World Records | work = Best Swimming | date = 3 August 2015 | url = http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/08/03/brasil-ganha-prata-com-nicholas-santos-em-tarde-de-2-recordes-mundiais/ | accessdate = 3 August 2015 | language = pt | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150923184246/http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/08/03/brasil-ganha-prata-com-nicholas-santos-em-tarde-de-2-recordes-mundiais/ | archive-date = 23 September 2015 | url-status = dead }}</ref> She also finished 11th in the [[Swimming at the 2015 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay]],<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 4x100-metre freestyle at 2015 Kazan | work = OmegaTiming | date = 2 August 2015 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010F020001003300FFFFFFFFFFFF02|accessdate = 2 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Morning of ups and downs at the swimming opening in Kazan|work = Best Swimming|date = 2 August 2015|url = http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/08/02/manha-de-altos-e-baixos-na-abertura-da-natacao-em-kazan/|accessdate = 2 August 2015|language = pt|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150923184238/http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/08/02/manha-de-altos-e-baixos-na-abertura-da-natacao-em-kazan/|archive-date = 23 September 2015|url-status = dead}}</ref> 14th in the [[Swimming at the 2015 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay]],<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 4x100-metre medley at 2015 Kazan | work = OmegaTiming | date = 9 August 2015 | url = http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010F020001043900FFFFFFFFFFFF02 | accessdate = 9 August 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170803165826/http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010F020001043900FFFFFFFFFFFF02 | archive-date = 3 August 2017 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Last heats day in Kazan|work = Best Swimming|date = 9 August 2015|url = http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/08/09/ultimo-dia-de-eliminatorias-em-kazan/|accessdate = 9 August 2015|language = pt|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150923184316/http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/08/09/ultimo-dia-de-eliminatorias-em-kazan/|archive-date = 23 September 2015|url-status = dead}}</ref> and 16th in the [[Swimming at the 2015 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre freestyle|Women's 50 metre freestyle]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 50-metre freestyle at 2015 Kazan | work = OmegaTiming | date = 8 August 2015 | url = http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010F020001001401FFFFFFFFFFFF02|accessdate = 8 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt the Open tournament held in [[Palho\u00e7a]], she broke the [[List of South American records in swimming|South American record]] in the 100-metre freestyle, with a time of 54.26.<ref>{{cite web|title = Etiene surprises with the 100-metre freestyle index: \"a case to think\"|work=Globoesporte|date = 18 December 2015|url = http://globoesporte.globo.com/natacao/noticia/2015/12/etiene-se-surpreende-com-indice-nos-100m-livre-um-caso-se-pensar.html|accessdate = 18 December 2015|language=pt}}</ref>\n\n===2016 Summer Olympics===\nAt the [[2016 Summer Olympics]], she went to the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 50 metre freestyle|Women's 50 metre freestyle]] final, finishing 8th.<ref>{{cite web|title = Etiene thank fans, but asks: \"Brazil, have patience with us\"|publisher=SPORTV|date = 13 August 2016|url = http://sportv.globo.com/site/programas/rio-2016/noticia/2016/08/etiene-agradece-torcida-mas-pede-brasil-tenha-paciencia-com-gente.html|accessdate =17 August 2016|language=pt}}</ref> She broke the South American record with a time of 24.45 in semifinals.<ref>{{cite web|title = Etiene Medeiros faz melhor tempo da carreira e avan\u00e7a \u00e0 final dos 50m livre|trans-title = Etiene Medeiros does the best time of her career and advances to the 50-metre freestyle final|work=Globoesporte|date = 12 August 2016|url = http://globoesporte.globo.com/olimpiadas/natacao/noticia/2016/08/etiene-medeiros-faz-melhor-tempo-da-carreira-e-avanca-final-dos-50m-livre.html|accessdate =12 August 2016|language=pt}}</ref> She also competed in the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 100 metre freestyle|Women's 100 metre freestyle]], finishing 16th in the semifinals;<ref>{{cite web|title = Etiene is the last one on her battery, and is out the 100m freestyle final|work=Terra|date = 10 August 2016|url = https://esportes.terra.com.br/esportes-aquaticos/etiene-fica-em-ultimo-em-bateria-e-esta-fora-da-final-dos-100m-livre,290e30720e41215542f8ca68d8a13328mh0f8dnl.html|accessdate =17 August 2016|language=pt}}</ref> in the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|Women's 100 metre backstroke]], finishing 25th;<ref>{{cite web|title = \"Today I swam badly,\" Etienne recognizes after elimination in the 100m backstroke|work=Globoesporte|date = 7 August 2016|url = http://globoesporte.globo.com/olimpiadas/natacao/noticia/2016/08/hoje-eu-fui-mal-reconhece-etiene-apos-eliminacao-nos-100m-costas.html#atleta-etiene-medeiros|accessdate =17 August 2016|language=pt}}</ref> and in the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay]], finishing 11th.<ref>{{cite web|title = Etiene Medeiros back to swim well and advance in the 100m freestyle: \"It left a top weight of me\"|work=Globoesporte|date = 10 August 2016|url = http://globoesporte.globo.com/olimpiadas/natacao/noticia/2016/08/etiene-medeiros-volta-nadar-bem-e-avanca-semifinais-dos-100m-livre.html|accessdate =17 August 2016|language=pt}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u2013present===\nOn 13 September 2016, at the Jos\u00e9 Finkel Trophy (short course competition), she broke the South American record in the 50-metre freestyle, with a time of 23.88.<ref>{{cite web|title = Etiene bate recorde sul-americano dos 50m livre e obt\u00e9m \u00edndice para Mundial|work=Globoesporte|date = 14 September 2016|url = http://globoesporte.globo.com/natacao/noticia/2016/09/etiene-bate-recorde-sul-americano-dos-50m-livre-e-obtem-indice-para-mundial.html|accessdate = 5 May 2017|language=pt}}</ref> She came close to beating the Americas record (23.82 of [[Dara Torres]]).\n\nOn 11 December 2016, participating in the [[2016 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)]] in Windsor, Canada, Medeiros won the gold medal with time of 25.82, to repeat as the 50m backstroke champion.<ref>https://swimswam.com/2016-short-course-world-championships-day-five-finals-live-recap/</ref> Etiene also obtained a silver medal in the 4x50 medley relay on 8 December. In addition to Etiene, the Brazilian team was formed by Felipe Lima, Nicholas Santos and Larissa Oliveira. She also swam the 50m freestyle, qualifying for the semifinal with a time of 24.31, but gave up the race to focus on the others she was fighting. She had real medal chances in this event as well: in September, she did a time of 23.88, which would give her the silver medal in this Worlds if it was repeated.\n\nAt the [[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships|2017 World Aquatics Championships]] in [[Budapest]], in the [[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|Women's 50 metre backstroke]], she broke two times the [[List of Americas records in swimming|Americas record]], with 27.18 in the semifinals, and 27.14 in the final, to obtain her first gold medal.<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of the 50-metre backstroke semifinals at 2017 Budapest |work=OmegaTiming |date=27 July 2017 |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000111010A0202EB02FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |accessdate=27 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901165546/http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000111010A0202EB02FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |archive-date=1 September 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of the 50-metre backstroke final at 2017 Budapest |work=OmegaTiming |date=27 July 2017 |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000111010A0202EB04FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |accessdate=27 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207231607/http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000111010A0202EB04FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |archive-date=7 February 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> She was only 8 hundredths of a second off Zhao Jing's world record, obtained at the super-suits era. Medeiros became the first Brazilian woman to win gold medal at a World Championships in long course. She also finished 21st in the [[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre freestyle|Women's 50 metre freestyle]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of the 50-metre freestyle at 2017 Budapest |work=OmegaTiming |date=29 July 2017 |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000111010A0201EB01FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |accessdate=27 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810074650/http://www.omegatiming.com/file/download/?id=000111010A0201EB01FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |archive-date=10 August 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)]] in [[Hangzhou]], [[China]], Medeiros came to try her third world title of the [[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|Women's 50 metre backstroke]]. However, in the semifinal of the event, she slipped in the start, losing the place in the final.<ref>{{cite web|title=Etiene Medeiros slides and stays out of the 50m backstroke final|work=UOL |date=14 December 2018 |url=https://esporte.uol.com.br/ultimas-noticias/efe/2018/12/14/etiene-medeiros-escorrega-e-fica-fora-da-final-dos-50m-costas.htm |accessdate=16 December 2018 |language=pt }}</ref> Then, she dedicated herself to the [[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 50 metre freestyle|Women's 50 metre freestyle]], where she was the South American record holder: Medeiros equaled the Americas record in the semifinal with a time of 23.82<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of the 50-metre freestyle semifinals at 2018 Hangzhou |work=OmegaTiming |date=15 December 2018 |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000112010C0201EB02FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref>, and in the final, she won an unprecedented bronze medal for Brazil in this event, beating the [[List of Americas records in swimming|Americas Record]], with a time of 23.76.<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of the 50-metre freestyle final at 2018 Hangzhou |work=OmegaTiming |date=16 December 2018 |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000112010C0201EB04FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref> She also finished 5th in the [[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Mixed 4 \u00d7 50 metre freestyle relay|Mixed 4 \u00d7 50 metre freestyle relay]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of the Mixed 4x50-metre freestyle at 2018 Hangzhou |work=OmegaTiming |date=12 December 2018 |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000112010C0301F604FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |accessdate=25 December 2018}}</ref>, 9th in the [[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Mixed 4 \u00d7 50 metre medley relay|Mixed 4 \u00d7 50 metre medley relay]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of the Mixed 4x50-metre medley at 2018 Hangzhou |work=OmegaTiming |date=13 December 2018 |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000112010C0305F601FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |accessdate=11 May 2019}}</ref>, and 21st in the [[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|Women's 100 metre backstroke]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of the 100-metre backstroke at 2018 Hangzhou |work=OmegaTiming |date=11 December 2018 |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000112010C0202EC01FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships|2019 World Aquatics Championships]] in [[Gwangju]], [[South Korea]], Medeiros won the silver medal in the [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|Women's 50 metre backstroke]]. It was her third consecutive medal in this event, in World Championships. <ref>{{cite web|title=Results of the 50 metre bakstroke at 2019 Gwangju|url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/00011301070202EB04FFFFFFFFFFFF01.pdf|publisher=Omega Timing|date=25 July 2019|accessdate=28 July 2019}}</ref> In the [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre freestyle|Women's 50 metre freestyle]], she came to try a final to develop for the 2020 Olympics. However, she failed to develop a good race on this occasion, finishing 23rd.<ref>{{cite web|title=Results of the 50 metre freestyle at 2019 Gwangju|url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/00011301070201EB01FFFFFFFFFFFF01.pdf |publisher=Omega Timing|date=27 July 2019|accessdate=28 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2019 Pan American Games]] held in [[Lima]], [[Peru]], Medeiros won the second gold medal in Brazilian women's swimming history (and her second individual gold) in the [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's 50 metre freestyle|Women's 50 metre freestyle]].<ref>[https://wrsd.lima2019.pe/PAG2019/resPAG2019/pdf/PAG2019/SWM/PAG2019_SWM_C74A_SWMW50MFR-------------FNL---------.pdf Women's 50m Freestyle - A Final]</ref> She won 5 medals in total: in addition to gold, she got two silver in the [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay]]<ref>[https://wrsd.lima2019.pe/PAG2019/resPAG2019/pdf/PAG2019/SWM/PAG2019_SWM_C73B2_SWMW4X100MFR----------FNL---------.pdf Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay Final]</ref> and [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games \u2013 Mixed 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|Mixed 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay]]<ref>[https://wrsd.lima2019.pe/PAG2019/resPAG2019/pdf/PAG2019/SWM/PAG2019_SWM_C73B1_SWMX4X100MFR----------FNL-000100--.pdf Mixed 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay Final]</ref>, and two bronzes in the [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|Women's 100 metre backstroke]]<ref>[https://wrsd.lima2019.pe/PAG2019/resPAG2019/pdf/PAG2019/SWM/PAG2019_SWM_C74A_SWMW100MBA------------FNL---------.pdf Women's 100m Backstroke - A Final]</ref> and the [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wrsd.lima2019.pe/PAG2019/resPAG2019/pdf/PAG2019/SWM/PAG2019_SWM_C73B1_SWMW4X100MMD----------FNL-000100--.pdf|title=FINAL RESULTS|date=10 August 2019|website=www.lima2019.pe|publisher=ATOS|access-date=10 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal bests==\nEtiene Medeiros is the current holder, or former holder, of the following records:<ref>{{cite web | title = Women's Swimming Records | work = CBDA | year = 2014 | url = http://www.cbda.org.br/recordes/oficiais-femininos-id-266 | accessdate = 20 September 2014 | language = pt | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121120074131/http://www.cbda.org.br/recordes/oficiais-femininos-id-266 | archivedate = 20 November 2012 }}</ref>\n\n;Long course (50 meters)\n* Americas record holder of the 50m backstroke: 27.14, time. Retrieved 27 July 2017\n* South American record holder of the 50m freestyle: 24.45, time. Retrieved 12 August 2016\n* Former South American record holder of the 100m freestyle: 54.26, time. Retrieved 18 December 2015\n* South American record holder of the 100m backstroke: 59.61, time. Retrieved 17 July 2015\n* South American record holder of the 4 \u00d7 100 m freestyle: 3:37.39, time. Retrieved 14 July 2015 with [[Larissa Oliveira]], [[Graciele Herrmann]] and [[Daynara de Paula]]\n\n;Short course (25 meters)\n* World record holder of the 50m backstroke: 25.67, time. Retrieved 7 December 2014\n* Americas record holder of the 50m freestyle: 23.76, time. Retrieved 16 December 2018\n* South American record holder of the 100m backstroke: 57.13, time. Retrieved 3 December 2014\n* Former South American record holder of the 4x50m freestyle: 1:39.85, time. Retrieved 1 September 2014 with [[Priscila de Souza]], [[J\u00e9ssica Cavalheiro]] and [[Daynara de Paula]]\n* South American record holder of the 4x50m medley: 1:46.47, time. Retrieved 5 December 2014 with [[Ana Carla Carvalho]], [[Daynara de Paula]] and [[Larissa Oliveira]]\n* South American record holder of the 4x50m mixed freestyle: 1:29.17, time. Retrieved 6 December 2014 with [[C\u00e9sar Cielo]], [[Jo\u00e3o de Lucca]] and [[Larissa Oliveira]]\n* South American record holder of the 4x50m mixed medley: 1:37.26, time. Retrieved 4 December 2014 with [[Felipe Fran\u00e7a]], [[Nicholas Santos]] and [[Larissa Oliveira]]\n\n==Honors and awards==\nMedeiros has received the following awards:\n* Medeiros was recognized by [[\u00c9poca (Brazilian magazine)|\u00c9poca]] magazine as one of the 100 most influential Brazilians in 2014 <ref>{{cite web|title= \u00c9poca \u2013 The most influential Brazilians in 2014|work= Best Swimming|url= http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/01/07/cesar-cielo-e-etiene-medeiros-na-lista-dos-100-mais-influentes-da-revista-epoca/|accessdate= 8 January 2015|language= pt|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150108175822/http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/01/07/cesar-cielo-e-etiene-medeiros-na-lista-dos-100-mais-influentes-da-revista-epoca/|archive-date= 8 January 2015|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of world records in swimming]]\n*[[List of Americas records in swimming]]\n*[[List of South American records in swimming]]\n*[[List of Brazilian records in swimming]]\n*[[List of World Swimming Championships (25 m) medalists (women)]]\n*[[World record progression 50 metres backstroke]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{FINA}}\n*{{Sports-reference}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|rec}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Sanja Jovanovi\u0107]]|title=[[World record progression 50 metres backstroke|Women's 50 metre backstroke<br />world record holder (short course)]]|years=7 December 2014 \u2013 present|after=''Incumbent''}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Footer World LC Champions 50m Backstroke Women}}\n{{Footer World SC Champions 50m Backstroke Women}}\n{{Footer World SC Champions 4x50m Medley Mixed}}\n{{Footer Pan American Champions 50 m Freestyle Women}}\n{{Footer Pan American Champions 100 m Backstroke Women}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Medeiros, Etiene}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Recife]]\n[[Category:Brazilian female swimmers]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2011 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2015 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2019 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:World Aquatics Championships medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)]]\n[[Category:World record holders in swimming]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games gold medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games bronze medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic swimmers of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:South American Games gold medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:South American Games silver medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:South American Games bronze medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:South American Games medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2014 South American Games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Brazilian swimmer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox swimmer\n| name           = Etiene Medeiros\n| image          = Etiene Medeiros, 2015 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size     = 250\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Etiene Medeiros in 2015\n| fullname       = Etiene Pires de Medeiros\n| national_team  = Brazil\n| strokes        = [[Backstroke]], [[Freestyle swimming|freestyle]]\n| coach          =\n| club           =\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1991|5|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Recife]], [[Pernambuco]], Brazil\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| height         = 1.68 m\n| weight         = 80 kg\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport|Women's swimming}}\n{{MedalCountry|Brazil}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FINA World Aquatics Championships|World Championships (LC)]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2017 World Aquatics Championships|2017 Budapest]]|[[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|50 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2015 World Aquatics Championships|2015 Kazan]]|[[Swimming at the 2015 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|50 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2019 World Aquatics Championships|2019 Gwangju]]|[[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|50 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FINA World Championships - Short Course|World Championships (SC)]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2014 Doha]]|[[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|50 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalGold|2014 Doha|[[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 4 \u00d7 50 metre mixed medley relay|4\u00d750 m mixed medley]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2016 Windsor]]|[[2016 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|50 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2016 Windsor|[[2016 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 4 \u00d7 50 metre mixed medley relay|4\u00d750 m mixed medley]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2014 Doha|[[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 4 \u00d7 50 metre mixed freestyle relay|4\u00d750 m mixed freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2018 Hangzhou]]|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 50 metre freestyle|50 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Pan American Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 Pan American Games|2015 Toronto]] | [[Swimming at the 2015 Pan American Games|100 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2019 Pan American Games|2019 Lima]] | [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games|50 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2015 Toronto|[[Swimming at the 2015 Pan American Games|50 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2019 Pan American Games|2019 Lima]] | [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games|4\u00d7100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games|2019 Lima]] | [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games - Mixed 4 x 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100 m mixed freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2015 Toronto| [[Swimming at the 2015 Pan American Games|4\u00d7100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2015 Toronto|[[Swimming at the 2015 Pan American Games|4\u00d7100 m medley]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games|2019 Lima]] | [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|100 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2019 Pan American Games|2019 Lima]] | [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m medley]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[South American Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 South American Games|2014 Santiago]] |[[Swimming at the 2014 South American Games|4\u00d7100 m medley]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2014 Santiago |[[Swimming at the 2014 South American Games|100 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2014 Santiago |[[Swimming at the 2014 South American Games|100 m butterfly]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FINA World Junior Swimming Championships|World Junior Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2008 FINA Youth World Swimming Championships|2008 Monterrey]] |[[2008 FINA Youth World Swimming Championships|50 m backstroke]]}}\n}}\n{{Portuguese name|Pires|de Medeiros}}\n'''Etiene Pires de Medeiros''' (born 24 May 1991) is a Brazilian competitive [[Swimming (sport)|swimmer]] who participates in backstroke and freestyle events.<ref>{{cite web|title = UOL profile|work = UOL|year = 2011|url = http://pan.uol.com.br/2011/atletas-brasileiros/etiene-medeiros/index.htm|archive-url = https://archive.today/20130424084129/http://pan.uol.com.br/2011/atletas-brasileiros/etiene-medeiros/index.htm|url-status = dead|archive-date = 24 April 2013|accessdate = 17 April 2013|language = pt}}</ref> Widely regarded as the best Brazilian woman swimmer of all time, Medeiros was the first Brazilian to win an individual gold medal in a [[FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|World Championship]] (long and short course) and [[Pan American Games]], and the first to be a world record-holder in the modern era (only [[Maria Lenk]] in 1939 had accomplished this feat)\n\n==International career==\n===2008\u201312===\nAt 17 years old, Etiene Medeiros won the silver medal in the 50-metre backstroke at the [[2008 FINA Youth World Swimming Championships]] in [[Monterrey]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Closing with the female swimming in high | work = CBDA | date = 21 November 2010 | url = http://www.cbda.org.br/noticias/encerramento-com-a-natacao-feminina-em-alta|accessdate = 17 April 2013|language=pt}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2009 World Aquatics Championships]] in [[Rome]], she finished 21st in the 50-metre backstroke.<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 50-metre backstroke at 2009 Rome | work = OmegaTiming | date = 29 July 2009 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=0001090B002A000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01|accessdate = 17 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nMedeiros was at the [[2010 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)]] in [[Dubai]], where she finished 17th in the 50-metre backstroke <ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 50-metre backstroke at 2010 Dubai | work = OmegaTiming | date = 18 December 2010 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010A000040000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01|accessdate = 17 April 2013}}</ref> and 30th in the 100-metre backstroke.<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 100-metre backstroke at 2010 Dubai | work = OmegaTiming | date = 15 December 2010 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010A000005000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 | accessdate = 17 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nShe joined the national delegation which attended the [[2011 World Aquatics Championships]] in [[Shanghai]], [[China]], winning the vacancy after the positive doping of [[Fabiola Molina]]. Etiene finished 43rd in the 100-metre backstroke, with a time of 1:05.18.<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 100-metre backstroke at the 2011 Shanghai | work = OmegaTiming | date = 25 July 2011 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010B0D0012000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01| accessdate = 17 April 2013}}</ref> She also swam the 50-metre backstroke, where she finished 25th<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 50-metre backstroke at the 2011 Shanghai | work = OmegaTiming | date = 27 July 2011 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010B0D002D000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01| accessdate = 17 April 2013}}</ref> and in the 4\u00d7100-metre medley, where she finished 17th.<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 4\u00d7100-metre medley at 2011 Shanghai | work = OmegaTiming | date = 30 July 2011 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010B0D0059000000FFFFFFFFFFFF01 | accessdate = 17 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2011 Pan American Games]], Etiene finished 10th in the 100-metre backstroke heats, and did not go to the final.<ref>{{cite web | title = Fabiola Molina wins the 100-metre backstroke and go to the final | work = Lancenet | date = 16 October 2011 | url = http://www.lancenet.com.br/minuto/Fabiola-Molina-vence-eliminatoria-costas_0_573542677.html | accessdate = 17 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nShe was at the [[2012 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)]] in [[Istanbul]], where she finished 10th in the 50-metre backstroke <ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 50-metre backstroke at 2012 Istanbul | work = OmegaTiming | date = 15 December 2012 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010C010D01011A01FFFFFFFFFFFF02|accessdate = 17 April 2013}}</ref> and 28th in the 100-metre backstroke.<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 100-metre backstroke at 2012 Istanbul | work = OmegaTiming | date = 12 December 2012 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010C010D01011B00FFFFFFFFFFFF02 | accessdate = 17 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2013\u201316===\nIn January 2013, she moved to S\u00e3o Paulo and start work with Coach Fernando Vanzella in club SESI-SP.\nIn April 2013, she won the Maria Lenk Trophy in Brazil, with a time of 27.88 seconds in the 50-metre backstroke, best mark of her life, and one of the best times of the year in the proof.<ref>{{cite web | title = Maria Lenk Trophy 2013: Jo\u00e3o is the best of 2013 | work = CBDA | date = 27 April 2013 | url = http://www.cbda.org.br/noticias/trofeu-maria-lenk-2013-joao-e-o-melhor-de-2013 | accessdate = 31 July 2013 | language = pt | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130702163851/http://www.cbda.org.br/noticias/trofeu-maria-lenk-2013-joao-e-o-melhor-de-2013 | archive-date = 2 July 2013 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Kazan 2015 - Etiene Medeiros.jpg|thumbnail|200px|Medeiros in Kazan 2015]]\n\nAt the [[2013 World Aquatics Championships]] in [[Barcelona]], she finished 21st in the [[Swimming at the 2013 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|100-metre backstroke]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Ahead of Lochte, Nicolas Oliveira goes to semis after 6 months out of the pool | publisher = SPORTV | date = 29 July 2013 | url = http://sportv.globo.com/site/eventos/mundial-de-esportes-aquaticos/noticia/2013/07/frente-de-lochte-nicolas-oliveira-vai-semis-apos-6-meses-fora-da-piscina.html| accessdate = 29 July 2013|language=pt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 100-metre backstroke at 2013 Barcelona | work = OmegaTiming | date = 29 July 2013 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010D020101011B00FFFFFFFFFFFF02|accessdate = 29 July 2013}}</ref> In the [[Swimming at the 2013 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|50-metre backstroke]], qualified for the final with the fifth fastest time, 27.89 seconds, one hundredth of her personal best.<ref>{{cite web | title = Etiene Medeiros goes to the 50-metre backstroke final with 5th best time | work = UOL | date = 31 July 2013 | url = http://esporte.uol.com.br/ultimas-noticias/afp/2013/07/31/etiene-medeiros-vai-a-final-dos-50m-costas-com-5-melhor-tempo.htm| accessdate = 31 July 2013|language=pt}}</ref> In the final, she finished in 4th place, with a time of 27.83 seconds, her personal best, getting the best placement of a Brazilian woman in the World Championships.<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 50-metre backstroke at 2013 Barcelona | work = OmegaTiming | date = 1 August 2013 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010D020101011A02FFFFFFFFFFFF02|accessdate = 1 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Glasses break, but Etienne reaches historic fourth place in Barcelona| publisher = SPORTV | date = 1 August 2013 | url = http://sportv.globo.com/site/eventos/mundial-de-esportes-aquaticos/noticia/2013/08/oculos-quebra-mas-etiene-consegue-quarto-lugar-historico-em-barcelona.html|accessdate = 1 August 2013|language=pt}}</ref> She also finished 12th in the [[Swimming at the 2013 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100-metre medley]], along with [[Daynara de Paula]], [[Larissa Oliveira]] and [[Beatriz Travalon]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 4\u00d7100-metre medley at 2013 Barcelona | work = OmegaTiming | date = 4 August 2013 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010D020101043900FFFFFFFFFFFF02|accessdate = 4 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2014 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships]] in [[Gold Coast, Queensland]], she finished 5th in the 4x100-metre freestyle relay, along with Graciele Herrmann, Daynara de Paula and Alessandra Marchioro; 5th in the 4x100-metre medley relay, along with Graciele Herrmann, Ana Carla Carvalho and Daynara de Paula; 6th in the 50-metre freestyle; 7th in the 100-metre butterfly; and 11th in the 100-metre backstroke.<ref>{{cite web | title = Fratus won gold in the 50m freestyle with the Pan-Pacific record | work = CBDA | date = 24 August 2014 | url = http://www.cbda.org.br/noticias/fratus-e-ouro-nos-50m-livre-com-recorde-do-pan-pacifico|accessdate =20 September 2014|language=pt}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 September 2014, participating in the [[Jos\u00e9 Finkel Trophy]] (short course competition) in [[Guaratinguet\u00e1]], Medeiros broke three South American records: in the 50-metre freestyle with a time of 24.15, in the 50-metre backstroke with a time of 26.41, and in the 100-metre backstroke with a time of 57.53.<ref>{{cite web | title = Miguel Valente does best time in the world in the year and Etiene hits her fourth South American record | work = CBDA | date = 4 September 2014 | url = http://www.cbda.org.br/noticias/miguel-valente-faz-melhor-tempo-do-mundo-no-ano-e-etiene-bateu-seu-quarto-recorde-sul-americano | accessdate = 20 September 2014|language=pt}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 December 2014, participating in the [[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)]] in Doha, Qatar, Medeiros broke the world record in the 50-metre backstroke with a time of 25.67.<ref>{{cite web | title = BRAZIL\u2019S ETIENE MEDEIROS BREAKS 50 BACKSTROKE WORLD RECORD IN DOHA | work = swimswam| date = 7 December 2014 | url = http://swimswam.com/brazils-etiene-medeiros-breaks-50-backstroke-world-record-doha/ | accessdate = 7 December 2014 }}</ref> Medeiros was the first woman in Brazil to get an individual medal in World Championships, and the first to win a gold medal. Medeiros won 3 medals in the competition: the gold in the [[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|Women's 50 metre backstroke]], another gold in the [[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 4 \u00d7 50 metre mixed medley relay|4 \u00d7 50 metre mixed medley relay]] (along with Felipe Fran\u00e7a, Nicholas Santos and Larissa Oliveira), and a bronze medal in the [[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 4 \u00d7 50 metre mixed freestyle relay|4 \u00d7 50 metre mixed freestyle relay]] (along with Cesar Cielo, Jo\u00e3o de Lucca and Larissa Oliveira). On 3 December, in the 4 \u00d7 50 metre mixed medley relay, Medeiros opened the final with a time of 25.83, and Brazil won the race beating the South American record with a time of 1:37.26, only 0.09 seconds from beating USA's world record (1:37.17). On 6 December, in the 4 \u00d7 50 metre mixed freestyle relay, Brazil broke the South American record with a time of 1:29.17, only 4 hundredths slower than Russia, which won the silver medal. In the 50-metre backstroke, Medeiros broke the Americas record in the semifinal with a time of 25.99, and the World record in the final with a time of 25.67. Medeiros also broke 2 times the South American record in the  [[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|100 metre backstroke]], with a time of 57.36 at heats and 57.13 in the semifinals, finishing in 7th place in the final; and 2 times in [[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 50 metre medley relay|Women's 4 \u00d7 50 metre medley relay]], with a time of 1:47.20 at heats and 1:46.47 in the final, finishing in 5th place.<ref>{{cite web | title = Doha gives to Brazil the short pool crown | work = CBDA | date = 7 December 2014 | url = http://www.cbda.org.br/noticias/doha-da-ao-brasil-a-coroa-em-piscina-curta |accessdate = 12 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Full Results at 2014 Doha | work = OmegaTiming | date = 8 December 2014 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010E010DFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF05 |accessdate = 12 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt the Brazilian Open, in [[Rio de Janeiro]], she broke the Americas record in the 50-metre backstroke,  with a time of 27.37.<ref>{{cite web | title = Pinheros takes the leadership at the Brazilian Open | work = CBDA | date = 19 December 2014 | url = http://www.cbda.org.br/noticias/pinheiros-assume-a-lideranca-do-brasileiro-senior-e-do-open | accessdate = 19 December 2014|language=pt}}</ref> She also broke the South American record in the 50-metre freestyle, with a time of 24.74.<ref>{{cite web | title = Victorious end of year to the Brazilian Swimming | work = CBDA | date = 20 December 2014 | url = http://www.cbda.org.br/noticias/fim-de-ano-vitorioso-para-a-natacao-brasileira | accessdate = 20 December 2014|language=pt}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ouro e prata nos 100m nado costas. (22016177812).jpg|thumbnail|250px|[[Natalia de Luccas]] (left) and Etiene Medeiros, 2015]]\n\nAt the [[Swimming at the 2015 Pan American Games|2015 Pan American Games]] in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada, Medeiros made history again, winning the first gold medal in the history of Brazilian women's swimming at Pan American Games. In the [[Swimming at the 2015 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|Women's 100 metre backstroke]], she did a time of 59.61, a new Pan Am Games and South American record. An hour after the unprecedented gold, she won the silver medal in the [[Swimming at the 2015 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's 50 metre freestyle|Women's 50 metre freestyle]], with a new South American record, 24.55.<ref>{{cite web|title = Etiene Medeiros is the first Brazilian woman swimming champion at Pan American Games|work=ClicRBS|date = 18 July 2015|url = http://wp.clicrbs.com.br/brasilolimpico/2015/07/18/etiene-medeiros-e-a-primeira-nadadora-brasileira-campea-pan-americana/?topo=52,1,1,,171,e171|accessdate = 19 July 2015|language=pt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Historic day for Brazil women's swimming in the Pan|work = Best Swimming|date = 18 July 2015|url = http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/07/18/dia-historico-para-a-natacao-feminina-do-brasil-no-pan/|accessdate = 19 July 2015|language = pt|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150923184228/http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/07/18/dia-historico-para-a-natacao-feminina-do-brasil-no-pan/|archive-date = 23 September 2015|url-status = dead}}</ref> In this competition, she also helped the Brazilian team to win two bronze medals in the [[Swimming at the 2015 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay]] (this, breaking the South American record, with a time of 3:37.39)<ref>{{cite web|title = Brazil is gold in the 4x100m freestyle and Thiago Pereira opens count towards record|work=Globoesporte|date = 14 July 2015|url = http://globoesporte.globo.com/jogos-pan-americanos/noticia/2015/07/brasil-confirma-favoritismo-vence-revezamento-4x100m-e-fatura-o-ouro.html|accessdate = 19 July 2015|language=pt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = First day of five medals, and two gold medals to Brazil, but the party was Canadian|work = Best Swimming|date = 15 July 2015|url = http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/07/15/primeiro-dia-de-5-medalhas-e-2-ouros-para-o-brasil-mas-a-festa-foi-canadense/|accessdate = 19 July 2015|language = pt|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150721172457/http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/07/15/primeiro-dia-de-5-medalhas-e-2-ouros-para-o-brasil-mas-a-festa-foi-canadense/|archive-date = 21 July 2015|url-status = dead}}</ref> and [[Swimming at the 2015 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay]].<ref>{{cite web|title = Without Thiago Pereira, Brazilian relay closes swimming with gold|work=O Estado de S.Paulo|date = 18 July 2015|url = http://esportes.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,sem-thiago--revezamento-brasileiro-tem-grande-atuacao-e-fecha-natacao-com-ouro,1727975|accessdate = 19 July 2015|language=pt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = How it was the last day of the Pan in Toronto|work = Best Swimming|date = 19 July 2015|url = http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/07/19/como-foi-o-ultimo-dia-de-prova-do-pan-em-toronto/|accessdate = 19 July 2015|language = pt|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150721172503/http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/07/19/como-foi-o-ultimo-dia-de-prova-do-pan-em-toronto/|archive-date = 21 July 2015|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[Swimming at the 2015 World Aquatics Championships|2015 World Aquatics Championships]] in [[Kazan]], in the [[Swimming at the 2015 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|Women's 50 metre backstroke]], Etiene broke another paradigm by becoming the first Brazilian woman to climb the podium in a long-course World Championships. She won the silver medal, beating the Americas record with a time of 27.26.<ref>{{cite web | title = Silver in the 50m backstroke, Etiene is 1st in Brazil to rise to the podium of the World | work = Globoesporte | date = 6 August 2015 | url = http://globoesporte.globo.com/natacao/noticia/2015/08/prata-nos-50m-costas-etiene-e-1-do-brasil-subir-ao-podio-do-mundial.html|accessdate = 6 August 2015|language=pt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 50-metre backstroke at 2015 Kazan | work = OmegaTiming | date = 6 August 2015 | url = http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010F020001011A02FFFFFFFFFFFF02|accessdate = 6 August 2015}}</ref> In the [[Swimming at the 2015 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|Women's 100 metre backstroke]], she came close to go to the final, finishing in 9th place, with a time of 59.97.<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 100-metre backstroke at 2015 Kazan | work = OmegaTiming | date = 3 August 2015 | url = http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010F020001011B01FFFFFFFFFFFF02 | accessdate = 3 August 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170803163454/http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010F020001011B01FFFFFFFFFFFF02 | archive-date = 3 August 2017 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Gold in Pan, Etiene stays in ninth place and doesn't go to the 100m backstroke final at the World Championships|publisher=ESPN|date = 3 August 2015|url = http://espn.uol.com.br/noticia/532973_ouro-no-pan-etiene-fica-em-nono-e-nao-vai-a-final-dos-100m-costas-no-mundial|accessdate = 3 August 2015|language=pt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Brazil wins silver with Nicholas Santos, in an evening with 2 World Records | work = Best Swimming | date = 3 August 2015 | url = http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/08/03/brasil-ganha-prata-com-nicholas-santos-em-tarde-de-2-recordes-mundiais/ | accessdate = 3 August 2015 | language = pt | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150923184246/http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/08/03/brasil-ganha-prata-com-nicholas-santos-em-tarde-de-2-recordes-mundiais/ | archive-date = 23 September 2015 | url-status = dead }}</ref> She also finished 11th in the [[Swimming at the 2015 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay]],<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 4x100-metre freestyle at 2015 Kazan | work = OmegaTiming | date = 2 August 2015 | url = http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010F020001003300FFFFFFFFFFFF02|accessdate = 2 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Morning of ups and downs at the swimming opening in Kazan|work = Best Swimming|date = 2 August 2015|url = http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/08/02/manha-de-altos-e-baixos-na-abertura-da-natacao-em-kazan/|accessdate = 2 August 2015|language = pt|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150923184238/http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/08/02/manha-de-altos-e-baixos-na-abertura-da-natacao-em-kazan/|archive-date = 23 September 2015|url-status = dead}}</ref> 14th in the [[Swimming at the 2015 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay]],<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 4x100-metre medley at 2015 Kazan | work = OmegaTiming | date = 9 August 2015 | url = http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010F020001043900FFFFFFFFFFFF02 | accessdate = 9 August 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170803165826/http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010F020001043900FFFFFFFFFFFF02 | archive-date = 3 August 2017 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Last heats day in Kazan|work = Best Swimming|date = 9 August 2015|url = http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/08/09/ultimo-dia-de-eliminatorias-em-kazan/|accessdate = 9 August 2015|language = pt|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150923184316/http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/08/09/ultimo-dia-de-eliminatorias-em-kazan/|archive-date = 23 September 2015|url-status = dead}}</ref> and 16th in the [[Swimming at the 2015 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre freestyle|Women's 50 metre freestyle]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Results of the 50-metre freestyle at 2015 Kazan | work = OmegaTiming | date = 8 August 2015 | url = http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010F020001001401FFFFFFFFFFFF02|accessdate = 8 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt the Open tournament held in [[Palho\u00e7a]], she broke the [[List of South American records in swimming|South American record]] in the 100-metre freestyle, with a time of 54.26.<ref>{{cite web|title = Etiene surprises with the 100-metre freestyle index: \"a case to think\"|work=Globoesporte|date = 18 December 2015|url = http://globoesporte.globo.com/natacao/noticia/2015/12/etiene-se-surpreende-com-indice-nos-100m-livre-um-caso-se-pensar.html|accessdate = 18 December 2015|language=pt}}</ref>\n\n===2016 Summer Olympics===\nAt the [[2016 Summer Olympics]], she went to the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 50 metre freestyle|Women's 50 metre freestyle]] final, finishing 8th.<ref>{{cite web|title = Etiene thank fans, but asks: \"Brazil, have patience with us\"|publisher=SPORTV|date = 13 August 2016|url = http://sportv.globo.com/site/programas/rio-2016/noticia/2016/08/etiene-agradece-torcida-mas-pede-brasil-tenha-paciencia-com-gente.html|accessdate =17 August 2016|language=pt}}</ref> She broke the South American record with a time of 24.45 in semifinals.<ref>{{cite web|title = Etiene Medeiros faz melhor tempo da carreira e avan\u00e7a \u00e0 final dos 50m livre|trans-title = Etiene Medeiros does the best time of her career and advances to the 50-metre freestyle final|work=Globoesporte|date = 12 August 2016|url = http://globoesporte.globo.com/olimpiadas/natacao/noticia/2016/08/etiene-medeiros-faz-melhor-tempo-da-carreira-e-avanca-final-dos-50m-livre.html|accessdate =12 August 2016|language=pt}}</ref> She also competed in the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 100 metre freestyle|Women's 100 metre freestyle]], finishing 16th in the semifinals;<ref>{{cite web|title = Etiene is the last one on her battery, and is out the 100m freestyle final|work=Terra|date = 10 August 2016|url = https://esportes.terra.com.br/esportes-aquaticos/etiene-fica-em-ultimo-em-bateria-e-esta-fora-da-final-dos-100m-livre,290e30720e41215542f8ca68d8a13328mh0f8dnl.html|accessdate =17 August 2016|language=pt}}</ref> in the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|Women's 100 metre backstroke]], finishing 25th;<ref>{{cite web|title = \"Today I swam badly,\" Etienne recognizes after elimination in the 100m backstroke|work=Globoesporte|date = 7 August 2016|url = http://globoesporte.globo.com/olimpiadas/natacao/noticia/2016/08/hoje-eu-fui-mal-reconhece-etiene-apos-eliminacao-nos-100m-costas.html#atleta-etiene-medeiros|accessdate =17 August 2016|language=pt}}</ref> and in the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay]], finishing 11th.<ref>{{cite web|title = Etiene Medeiros back to swim well and advance in the 100m freestyle: \"It left a top weight of me\"|work=Globoesporte|date = 10 August 2016|url = http://globoesporte.globo.com/olimpiadas/natacao/noticia/2016/08/etiene-medeiros-volta-nadar-bem-e-avanca-semifinais-dos-100m-livre.html|accessdate =17 August 2016|language=pt}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u2013present===\nOn 13 September 2016, at the Jos\u00e9 Finkel Trophy (short course competition), she broke the South American record in the 50-metre freestyle, with a time of 23.88.<ref>{{cite web|title = Etiene bate recorde sul-americano dos 50m livre e obt\u00e9m \u00edndice para Mundial|work=Globoesporte|date = 14 September 2016|url = http://globoesporte.globo.com/natacao/noticia/2016/09/etiene-bate-recorde-sul-americano-dos-50m-livre-e-obtem-indice-para-mundial.html|accessdate = 5 May 2017|language=pt}}</ref> She came close to beating the Americas record (23.82 of [[Dara Torres]]).\n\nOn 11 December 2016, participating in the [[2016 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)]] in Windsor, Canada, Medeiros won the gold medal with time of 25.82, to repeat as the 50m backstroke champion.<ref>https://swimswam.com/2016-short-course-world-championships-day-five-finals-live-recap/</ref> Etiene also obtained a silver medal in the 4x50 medley relay on 8 December. In addition to Etiene, the Brazilian team was formed by Felipe Lima, Nicholas Santos and Larissa Oliveira. She also swam the 50m freestyle, qualifying for the semifinal with a time of 24.31, but gave up the race to focus on the others she was fighting. She had real medal chances in this event as well: in September, she did a time of 23.88, which would give her the silver medal in this Worlds if it was repeated.\n\nAt the [[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships|2017 World Aquatics Championships]] in [[Budapest]], in the [[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|Women's 50 metre backstroke]], she broke two times the [[List of Americas records in swimming|Americas record]], with 27.18 in the semifinals, and 27.14 in the final, to obtain her first gold medal.<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of the 50-metre backstroke semifinals at 2017 Budapest |work=OmegaTiming |date=27 July 2017 |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000111010A0202EB02FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |accessdate=27 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901165546/http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000111010A0202EB02FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |archive-date=1 September 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of the 50-metre backstroke final at 2017 Budapest |work=OmegaTiming |date=27 July 2017 |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000111010A0202EB04FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |accessdate=27 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207231607/http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000111010A0202EB04FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |archive-date=7 February 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> She was only 8 hundredths of a second off Zhao Jing's world record, obtained at the super-suits era. Medeiros became the first Brazilian woman to win gold medal at a World Championships in long course. She also finished 21st in the [[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre freestyle|Women's 50 metre freestyle]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of the 50-metre freestyle at 2017 Budapest |work=OmegaTiming |date=29 July 2017 |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000111010A0201EB01FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |accessdate=27 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810074650/http://www.omegatiming.com/file/download/?id=000111010A0201EB01FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |archive-date=10 August 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)]] in [[Hangzhou]], [[China]], Medeiros came to try her third world title of the [[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|Women's 50 metre backstroke]]. However, in the semifinal of the event, she slipped in the start, losing the place in the final.<ref>{{cite web|title=Etiene Medeiros slides and stays out of the 50m backstroke final|work=UOL |date=14 December 2018 |url=https://esporte.uol.com.br/ultimas-noticias/efe/2018/12/14/etiene-medeiros-escorrega-e-fica-fora-da-final-dos-50m-costas.htm |accessdate=16 December 2018 |language=pt }}</ref> Then, she dedicated herself to the [[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 50 metre freestyle|Women's 50 metre freestyle]], where she was the South American record holder: Medeiros equaled the Americas record in the semifinal with a time of 23.82<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of the 50-metre freestyle semifinals at 2018 Hangzhou |work=OmegaTiming |date=15 December 2018 |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000112010C0201EB02FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref>, and in the final, she won an unprecedented bronze medal for Brazil in this event, beating the [[List of Americas records in swimming|Americas Record]], with a time of 23.76.<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of the 50-metre freestyle final at 2018 Hangzhou |work=OmegaTiming |date=16 December 2018 |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000112010C0201EB04FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref> She also finished 5th in the [[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Mixed 4 \u00d7 50 metre freestyle relay|Mixed 4 \u00d7 50 metre freestyle relay]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of the Mixed 4x50-metre freestyle at 2018 Hangzhou |work=OmegaTiming |date=12 December 2018 |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000112010C0301F604FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |accessdate=25 December 2018}}</ref>, 9th in the [[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Mixed 4 \u00d7 50 metre medley relay|Mixed 4 \u00d7 50 metre medley relay]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of the Mixed 4x50-metre medley at 2018 Hangzhou |work=OmegaTiming |date=13 December 2018 |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000112010C0305F601FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |accessdate=11 May 2019}}</ref>, and 21st in the [[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|Women's 100 metre backstroke]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Results of the 100-metre backstroke at 2018 Hangzhou |work=OmegaTiming |date=11 December 2018 |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000112010C0202EC01FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships|2019 World Aquatics Championships]] in [[Gwangju]], [[South Korea]], Medeiros won the silver medal in the [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|Women's 50 metre backstroke]]. It was her third consecutive medal in this event, in World Championships. <ref>{{cite web|title=Results of the 50 metre bakstroke at 2019 Gwangju|url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/00011301070202EB04FFFFFFFFFFFF01.pdf|publisher=Omega Timing|date=25 July 2019|accessdate=28 July 2019}}</ref> In the [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre freestyle|Women's 50 metre freestyle]], she came to try a final to develop for the 2020 Olympics. However, she failed to develop a good race on this occasion, finishing 23rd.<ref>{{cite web|title=Results of the 50 metre freestyle at 2019 Gwangju|url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/00011301070201EB01FFFFFFFFFFFF01.pdf |publisher=Omega Timing|date=27 July 2019|accessdate=28 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2019 Pan American Games]] held in [[Lima]], [[Peru]], Medeiros won the second gold medal in Brazilian women's swimming history (and her second individual gold) in the [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's 50 metre freestyle|Women's 50 metre freestyle]]<ref>[https://wrsd.lima2019.pe/PAG2019/resPAG2019/pdf/PAG2019/SWM/PAG2019_SWM_C74A_SWMW50MFR-------------FNL---------.pdf Women's 50m Freestyle - A Final]</ref>. She won 5 medals in total: in addition to gold, she got two silver in the [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay]]<ref>[https://wrsd.lima2019.pe/PAG2019/resPAG2019/pdf/PAG2019/SWM/PAG2019_SWM_C73B2_SWMW4X100MFR----------FNL---------.pdf Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay Final]</ref> and [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games \u2013 Mixed 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|Mixed 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay]]<ref>[https://wrsd.lima2019.pe/PAG2019/resPAG2019/pdf/PAG2019/SWM/PAG2019_SWM_C73B1_SWMX4X100MFR----------FNL-000100--.pdf Mixed 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay Final]</ref>, and two bronzes in the [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|Women's 100 metre backstroke]]<ref>[https://wrsd.lima2019.pe/PAG2019/resPAG2019/pdf/PAG2019/SWM/PAG2019_SWM_C74A_SWMW100MBA------------FNL---------.pdf Women's 100m Backstroke - A Final]</ref> and the [[Swimming at the 2019 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wrsd.lima2019.pe/PAG2019/resPAG2019/pdf/PAG2019/SWM/PAG2019_SWM_C73B1_SWMW4X100MMD----------FNL-000100--.pdf|title=FINAL RESULTS|date=10 August 2019|website=www.lima2019.pe|publisher=ATOS|access-date=10 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal bests==\nEtiene Medeiros is the current holder, or former holder, of the following records:<ref>{{cite web | title = Women's Swimming Records | work = CBDA | year = 2014 | url = http://www.cbda.org.br/recordes/oficiais-femininos-id-266 | accessdate = 20 September 2014 | language = pt | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121120074131/http://www.cbda.org.br/recordes/oficiais-femininos-id-266 | archivedate = 20 November 2012 }}</ref>\n\n;Long course (50 meters)\n* Americas record holder of the 50m backstroke: 27.14, time. Retrieved 27 July 2017\n* South American record holder of the 50m freestyle: 24.45, time. Retrieved 12 August 2016\n* Former South American record holder of the 100m freestyle: 54.26, time. Retrieved 18 December 2015\n* South American record holder of the 100m backstroke: 59.61, time. Retrieved 17 July 2015\n* South American record holder of the 4 \u00d7 100 m freestyle: 3:37.39, time. Retrieved 14 July 2015 with [[Larissa Oliveira]], [[Graciele Herrmann]] and [[Daynara de Paula]]\n\n;Short course (25 meters)\n* World record holder of the 50m backstroke: 25.67, time. Retrieved 7 December 2014\n* Americas record holder of the 50m freestyle: 23.76, time. Retrieved 16 December 2018\n* South American record holder of the 100m backstroke: 57.13, time. Retrieved 3 December 2014\n* Former South American record holder of the 4x50m freestyle: 1:39.85, time. Retrieved 1 September 2014 with [[Priscila de Souza]], [[J\u00e9ssica Cavalheiro]] and [[Daynara de Paula]]\n* South American record holder of the 4x50m medley: 1:46.47, time. Retrieved 5 December 2014 with [[Ana Carla Carvalho]], [[Daynara de Paula]] and [[Larissa Oliveira]]\n* South American record holder of the 4x50m mixed freestyle: 1:29.17, time. Retrieved 6 December 2014 with [[C\u00e9sar Cielo]], [[Jo\u00e3o de Lucca]] and [[Larissa Oliveira]]\n* South American record holder of the 4x50m mixed medley: 1:37.26, time. Retrieved 4 December 2014 with [[Felipe Fran\u00e7a]], [[Nicholas Santos]] and [[Larissa Oliveira]]\n\n==Honors and awards==\nMedeiros has received the following awards:\n* Medeiros was recognized by [[\u00c9poca (Brazilian magazine)|\u00c9poca]] magazine as one of the 100 most influential Brazilians in 2014 <ref>{{cite web|title= \u00c9poca \u2013 The most influential Brazilians in 2014|work= Best Swimming|url= http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/01/07/cesar-cielo-e-etiene-medeiros-na-lista-dos-100-mais-influentes-da-revista-epoca/|accessdate= 8 January 2015|language= pt|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150108175822/http://www.bestswimming.com.br/2015/01/07/cesar-cielo-e-etiene-medeiros-na-lista-dos-100-mais-influentes-da-revista-epoca/|archive-date= 8 January 2015|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of world records in swimming]]\n*[[List of Americas records in swimming]]\n*[[List of South American records in swimming]]\n*[[List of Brazilian records in swimming]]\n*[[List of World Swimming Championships (25 m) medalists (women)]]\n*[[World record progression 50 metres backstroke]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{FINA}}\n*{{Sports-reference}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|rec}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Sanja Jovanovi\u0107]]|title=[[World record progression 50 metres backstroke|Women's 50 metre backstroke<br />world record holder (short course)]]|years=7 December 2014 \u2013 present|after=''Incumbent''}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Footer World LC Champions 50m Backstroke Women}}\n{{Footer World SC Champions 50m Backstroke Women}}\n{{Footer World SC Champions 4x50m Medley Mixed}}\n{{Footer Pan American Champions 50 m Freestyle Women}}\n{{Footer Pan American Champions 100 m Backstroke Women}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Medeiros, Etiene}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Recife]]\n[[Category:Brazilian female swimmers]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2011 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2015 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2019 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:World Aquatics Championships medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)]]\n[[Category:World record holders in swimming]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games gold medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games bronze medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic swimmers of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:South American Games gold medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:South American Games silver medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:South American Games bronze medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:South American Games medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2014 South American Games]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Etiene_Medeiros"}
{"title_page": "Ethnic plastic surgery", "text_new": "{{expert needed\n| 1 = Medicine & Social Psychology\n| talk = Expert\n| date = June 2015\n}}\n'''Ethnic plastic surgery''' or '''ethnic modification''',<ref name=\"brandeis\">[http://www.brandeis.edu/ethics/ethicalinquiry/2011/may.html Is \u201cEthnic Modification\u201d Surgery Ethical?]</ref> is [[plastic surgery]] intended to change an individual's appearance to look more or less like a particular [[race (human classification)|race]] or [[ethnicity]]. Popular plastic surgery procedures which may have an ethnically-motivated component include [[Rhinoplasty]] (nose surgery) and [[blepharoplasty]] (eyelid surgery).<ref name=\"wapo\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/25/AR2007052502387.html Cosmetic Surgery Goes Ethnic]</ref>\n\n[[Michael Jackson]]'s [[Michael Jackson's health and appearance|plastic surgery]] has been discussed in the context of ethnic plastic surgery.<ref name=\"psp\">[http://www.plasticsurgerypractice.com/2014/08/editor-ethnic-plastic-surgery-whats-name/ Ethnic Plastic Surgery: What\u2019s in a Name?]</ref> In her book ''Venus Envy: A History of Cosmetic Surgery'', Elizabeth Haiken devotes a chapter to \"The Michael Jackson Factor\" presenting \"[[Black People|black]], [[Asians|Asian]] and [[Jewish]] women who seek [[White Anglo-Saxon Protestant|WASP]] noses and [[Playboy]] breasts. They are caught in the vexed immigrants' dilemma of struggling not only to [[Keeping up with the Joneses|keep up with the Joneses]] but to look like them, too.\"<ref name=\"nytimes\">[https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/08/02/reviews/980802.02schillt.html America's Paint and Body Shop]</ref>\n\n==Ethical considerations==\n\nPlastic surgeons Chuma J. Chike-Obi, M.D., Kofi Boahene, M.D., and Anthony E. Brissett, M.D., F.A.C.S. distinguish between motivations of aesthetics and [[Racial transformation (individual)|racial transformation]] for patients of African descent seeking plastic surgery.  In their opinion, \"Patients whose desired surgical outcomes result in racial transformation should be educated about the potential risks of this objective, and these requests should generally be discouraged.\"<ref name = Chike-Obi>{{cite journal | author = Chike-Obi|display-authors=etal| year = 2012 | title = Tip Nuances for the Nose of African Descent | url = http://www.drboahene.com/Documents/tip%20rhinoplasty%20in%20african%20noses.pdf | format = PDF | journal = Facial Plast Surg | volume = 28 | issue = | pages = 194\u2013201 | doi=10.1055/s-0032-1309299}}</ref>\n\nFeminist scholars have split views on the subject. [[Christine Overall]], professor of philosophy at Queen's University, has written that personal racial transformation, or as she puts it \"transracialism\", belongs to a larger class of personal surgical interventions. This larger class includes [[transsexual]] identity change, [[body art]], [[cosmetic surgery]], [[Munchhausen syndrome]] and [[Labiaplasty]]. Her basic thesis is that the arguments against the ethical nature of racial transformation (e.g. \"it's not possible\", \"betrayal of group identity\", \"reinforces oppression\", etc.) stand or fall with the ethical arguments related to transsexual change. Basically, if it's OK for persons to change their gender, it's OK for persons to change their race.<ref name = \"Overall\">[http://www.pdcnet.org/pdc/bvdb.nsf/purchase?openform&fp=socphiltoday&id=socphiltoday_2004_0020_0000_0183_0196 Christine Overall, \"Transsexualism and 'Transracialism'\", Social Philosophy Today, vol 20, 2004, pp 183-193]</ref> [[Cressida Heyes]], professor of Philosophy of Gender and Sexuality at the University of Alberta, disagrees with Overall's schema.  Heyes feels that racial transformation is fundamentally different from gender transformation since race is also determined by ancestry, personal cultural history and societal definitions.  Hence ethical considerations of transracial surgery are different from ethical considerations in transsexual surgery.<ref name = \"Heyes\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1111/j.1467-9833.2006.00332.x | volume=37 | title=Changing Race, Changing Sex: The Ethics of Self-Transformation | year=2006 | journal=Journal of Social Philosophy | pages=266\u2013282 | author=Heyes Cressida J}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nIn the ''[[South Park]]'' episode \"[[Mr. Garrison's Fancy New Vagina]]\" Kyle undergoes an ethnic plastic surgery called \"negroplasty\" because he is too short for a basketball game.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Allophilia]]\n* [[Passing (racial identity)]]\n* [[Skin whitening]]\n* [[The Operated Jew]]\n* [[Health and appearance of Michael Jackson#Skin color|Racial transformation of Michael Jackson]]\n* [[Good hair]]\n* [[Martina Big]]\n* [[Fred Korematsu]]\n* [[Transracial (identity)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Racism topics}}\n\n[[Category:Plastic surgery]]\n[[Category:Race and society]]\n[[Category:Body modification process]]\n[[Category:Identity (social science)]]\n[[Category:Race (human categorization)]]\n[[Category:Conceptions of self]]\n[[Category:Ethically disputed medical practices]]\n[[Category:Body modification]]\n", "text_old": "{{expert needed\n| 1 = Medicine & Social Psychology\n| talk = Expert\n| date = June 2015\n}}\n'''Ethnic plastic surgery''' or '''ethnic modification''',<ref name=\"brandeis\">[http://www.brandeis.edu/ethics/ethicalinquiry/2011/may.html Is \u201cEthnic Modification\u201d Surgery Ethical?]</ref> is [[plastic surgery]] intended to change an individual's appearance to look more or less like a particular [[race (human classification)|race]] or [[ethnicity]]. Popular plastic surgery procedures which may have an ethnically-motivated component include [[Rhinoplasty]] (nose surgery) and [[blepharoplasty]] (eyelid surgery)<ref name=\"wapo\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/25/AR2007052502387.html Cosmetic Surgery Goes Ethnic]</ref>.\n\n[[Michael Jackson]]'s [[Michael Jackson's health and appearance|plastic surgery]] has been discussed in the context of ethnic plastic surgery.<ref name=\"psp\">[http://www.plasticsurgerypractice.com/2014/08/editor-ethnic-plastic-surgery-whats-name/ Ethnic Plastic Surgery: What\u2019s in a Name?]</ref> In her book ''Venus Envy: A History of Cosmetic Surgery'', Elizabeth Haiken devotes a chapter to \"The Michael Jackson Factor\" presenting \"[[Black People|black]], [[Asians|Asian]] and [[Jewish]] women who seek [[White Anglo-Saxon Protestant|WASP]] noses and [[Playboy]] breasts. They are caught in the vexed immigrants' dilemma of struggling not only to [[Keeping up with the Joneses|keep up with the Joneses]] but to look like them, too.\"<ref name=\"nytimes\">[https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/08/02/reviews/980802.02schillt.html America's Paint and Body Shop]</ref>\n\n==Ethical considerations==\n\nPlastic surgeons Chuma J. Chike-Obi, M.D., Kofi Boahene, M.D., and Anthony E. Brissett, M.D., F.A.C.S. distinguish between motivations of aesthetics and [[Racial transformation (individual)|racial transformation]] for patients of African descent seeking plastic surgery.  In their opinion, \"Patients whose desired surgical outcomes result in racial transformation should be educated about the potential risks of this objective, and these requests should generally be discouraged.\"<ref name = Chike-Obi>{{cite journal | author = Chike-Obi|display-authors=etal| year = 2012 | title = Tip Nuances for the Nose of African Descent | url = http://www.drboahene.com/Documents/tip%20rhinoplasty%20in%20african%20noses.pdf | format = PDF | journal = Facial Plast Surg | volume = 28 | issue = | pages = 194\u2013201 | doi=10.1055/s-0032-1309299}}</ref>\n\nFeminist scholars have split views on the subject. [[Christine Overall]], professor of philosophy at Queen's University, has written that personal racial transformation, or as she puts it \"transracialism\", belongs to a larger class of personal surgical interventions. This larger class includes [[transsexual]] identity change, [[body art]], [[cosmetic surgery]], [[Munchhausen syndrome]] and [[Labiaplasty]]. Her basic thesis is that the arguments against the ethical nature of racial transformation (e.g. \"it's not possible\", \"betrayal of group identity\", \"reinforces oppression\", etc.) stand or fall with the ethical arguments related to transsexual change. Basically, if it's OK for persons to change their gender, it's OK for persons to change their race.<ref name = \"Overall\">[http://www.pdcnet.org/pdc/bvdb.nsf/purchase?openform&fp=socphiltoday&id=socphiltoday_2004_0020_0000_0183_0196 Christine Overall, \"Transsexualism and 'Transracialism'\", Social Philosophy Today, vol 20, 2004, pp 183-193]</ref> [[Cressida Heyes]], professor of Philosophy of Gender and Sexuality at the University of Alberta, disagrees with Overall's schema.  Heyes feels that racial transformation is fundamentally different from gender transformation since race is also determined by ancestry, personal cultural history and societal definitions.  Hence ethical considerations of transracial surgery are different from ethical considerations in transsexual surgery.<ref name = \"Heyes\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1111/j.1467-9833.2006.00332.x | volume=37 | title=Changing Race, Changing Sex: The Ethics of Self-Transformation | year=2006 | journal=Journal of Social Philosophy | pages=266\u2013282 | author=Heyes Cressida J}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nIn the ''[[South Park]]'' episode \"[[Mr. Garrison's Fancy New Vagina]]\" Kyle undergoes an ethnic plastic surgery called \"negroplasty\" because he is too short for a basketball game.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Allophilia]]\n* [[Passing (racial identity)]]\n* [[Skin whitening]]\n* [[The Operated Jew]]\n* [[Health and appearance of Michael Jackson#Skin color|Racial transformation of Michael Jackson]]\n* [[Good hair]]\n* [[Martina Big]]\n* [[Fred Korematsu]]\n* [[Transracial (identity)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Racism topics}}\n\n[[Category:Plastic surgery]]\n[[Category:Race and society]]\n[[Category:Body modification process]]\n[[Category:Identity (social science)]]\n[[Category:Race (human categorization)]]\n[[Category:Conceptions of self]]\n[[Category:Ethically disputed medical practices]]\n[[Category:Body modification]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ethnic_plastic_surgery"}
{"title_page": "Ethnic groups in Nepal", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=March 2018}}\n{{Pie chart\n|thumb = right\n|caption = Ethnic groups of Nepal (2011)<ref name=\"CIATONGA\">{{cite web|url= https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/np.html|title= South Asia ::NEPAL|publisher= CIA The World Factbook}}</ref>\n|label1 = [[Kshetri]]\n|value1 = 16.6\n|color1 = red\n|label2 = [[Brahman-Hill]]\n|value2 = 12.2\n|color2 = Orange\n|label3 = [[Magar people|Magar]]\n|value3 = 7.1\n|color3 = Green\n|label4 = [[Tharu people|Tharu]]\n|value4 = 6.6\n|color4 = Chartreuse\n|label5 = [[Tamang]]\n|value5 = 5.8\n|color5 = DodgerBlue\n|label6 = [[Newar]]\n|value6 = 5\n|color6 = HotPink\n|label7 = [[Kami (caste)|Kami]]\n|value7 = 4.8\n|color7 = Black\n|label8 = [[Nepalese Muslims]]\n|value8 = 4.4\n|color8 = silver\n|label9 = [[Yadav]]\n|value9 = 4\n|color9 = cyan\n|label10 = [[Rai (ethnic group)|Rai]]\n|value10 = 2.3\n|color10 = Yellow\n|label11 = Others\n|value11 = 31.2\n|color11 = skyblue\n}}\n[[File:Thapa boy.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Kshetri]], the largest caste group in Nepal]]\n\n[[File:Sakela_ladies.JPG|thumb| Rai ethnic group in Nepal]] \n[[File:Indigenous magar girls of Nepal.JPG|thumb|Indigenous [[Magars|Magar]] girls of Nepal; Magars are the largest [[Adivasi|Janjatis]] in Nepal]]\n[[File:JanakpurChhathParvaFestival.jpg|thumb|[[Madhesi people|Madheshis]] celebrating [[Chhath]] in Janakpur. Madheshis are a community of different caste groups of Terai in Nepal.]]\n\n'''Ethnic groups in Nepal''' are a product of both the colonial and state-building eras of [[Nepal]]. The groups are delineated using language, ethnic identity or the [[caste system in Nepal]]. They are categorized by common [[culture]] and [[endogamy]]. Endogamy carves out ethnic groups in Nepal.{{cn|date=April 2019}}\n\n==Linguistic groups==\n[[File:Dashain Tika 02.JPG|thumb|[[Khas people]] celebrating [[Dashain]] festival; Khas are the largest ethno-linguistic group in Nepal comprising [[Bahun]], [[Chhetri]], [[Kami (caste)|Kami]], [[Damai]] and other [[Dalit]]s]]\nNepal's diverse linguistic heritage evolved from three major language groups: [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan]], [[Tibeto-Burman languages]], and various [[indigenous language]] isolates. According to the 2001 national census, ninety two different living languages are spoken in Nepal (a ninety third category was \"unspecified\"). Based upon the 2011 census, the major languages spoken in Nepal are Nepali , Maithili and Bhojpuri.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cbs.gov.np/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/Summary-Nepali.pdf |format=PDF |title=Official Summary of Census |year=2011 |work=Central Bureau of Statistics, Nepal |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121202145804/http://cbs.gov.np/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/Summary-Nepali.pdf |archivedate=2 December 2012 }}</ref>\n\nSince Nepal's unification, various indigenous languages have come under threat of extinction as the government of Nepal has marginalized their use through strict policies designed to promote Nepali as the official language. Indigenous languages which have gone extinct or are critically threatened include Byangsi, Chonkha, and Longaba. Since democracy was restored in 1990, however, the government has worked to improve the marginalization of these languages. Tribhuvan University began surveying and recording threatened languages in 2010 and the government intends to use this information to include more languages on the next Nepalese census.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tumbahang|first=Govinda Bahadur|year=2010|title=Marginalization of indigenous languages of Nepal|url=|journal=Contributions to Nepalese Studies|volume=37|pages=69|via=Expanded Academic}}</ref>\n\n==Social status==\n[[File:SunuwarMaleFemale.jpg|thumbnail|[[Sunuwar]], a division of [[Kirati people]]; one of the largest ethnic cluster in Eastern Nepal]]\n[[Pahari people|Pahari]] Hill Hindus of the [[Khas|Khas Gorkha]] tribe ([[Bahun|Brahmin/Bahun]] and [[Chhetri]] castes) and the [[Newar people|Newar ethnicity]] dominated the civil service, the judiciary and upper ranks of the army throughout the [[Kingdom of Nepal|Shah regime]] (1768\u20132008). Nepali was the national language and [[Sanskrit]] became a required school subject. Children who spoke Nepali natively and who were exposed to Sanskrit had much better chances of passing the national examinations at the end of high school, which meant they had better employment prospects and could continue into higher education.\n\nOn the other hand, children who natively spoke local languages of the [[Madhesh]] and [[Hill Region|Hills]], or Tibetan dialects prevailing in the high mountains were at a considerable disadvantage. This history of exclusion coupled with poor prospects for improvement created grievances that encouraged many in ethnic communities such as [[Madhesi people|Madhesi]], [[Tharu people|Tharu]] and [[Kham Magar]] to support the [[Unified Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist)]] and various other armed Maoist opposition groups such as the [[JTMM]] during and after the [[Nepalese Civil War]]. The negotiated end to this war forced King [[Gyanendra of Nepal|Gyanendra]] to abdicate in 2008.\n\nIssues of ethnic and regional equity have tended to dominate the agenda of the new republican government and continue to be divisive. Today, even after the end of a 10-year-old Maoist conflict, the upper caste dominates every field in Nepal. Specifically, Brahmin and Chhetri (Indo-Aryan) have advantages. Although Newars are low in numbers, their urban living habitat gives them a competitive advantage. Thus, Newars are at the top of the Human Development Index. From a [[Gender inequality in Nepal|gender perspective]], Newari women are the most literate and lead in every sector. Brahmin and Chhetri women have experienced less social and economic mobility compared to Newari women. Specifically, Brahmin women experience less equality due to their predominately rural living conditions which deprives them of access to certain educational and healthcare benefits.<ref name=\"OCHA1\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.internal-displacement.org/8025708F004CE90B/(httpDocuments)/B66F206172F49BE4C12572D50030C3F0/$file/OCHA+overview+no+12+April+07.pdf |format=PDF |title=OCHA Nepal \u2013 Situation Overview |volume=Issue 12 |date=April 2007 |publisher=[[OCHA]] |accessdate=2011-05-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091113112940/http://www.internal-displacement.org/8025708F004CE90B/(httpDocuments)/B66F206172F49BE4C12572D50030C3F0/$file/OCHA+overview+no+12+April+07.pdf |archivedate=13 November 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"OCHA2\">{{cite journal|url=http://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/2E89F2121C2C57A24925733F000F4F21-Full_report.pdf |format=PDF |title=OCHA Nepal \u2013 Situation Overview |volume=Issue 16 |date=July\u2013August 2007 |publisher=[[OCHA]] |accessdate=2011-05-07}}</ref><ref name=\"OCHA3\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.internal-displacement.org/8025708F004CE90B/(httpDocuments)/5CC0BE0C971587F2C1257496004A9B9E/$file/ocha+sitrep+12+july08.pdf |format=PDF |title=OCHA Nepal \u2013 Situation Overview |volume=Issue 30 |date=June\u2013July 2008 |publisher=[[OCHA]] |accessdate=2011-05-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100218090410/http://www.internal-displacement.org/8025708F004CE90B/(httpDocuments)/5CC0BE0C971587F2C1257496004A9B9E/$file/ocha+sitrep+12+july08.pdf |archivedate=18 February 2010 }}</ref><ref name=\"Him-ext\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thehimalayantimes.com/fullNews.php?headline=Body+of+murder+victim+found+in+Gulmi&NewsID=266104 |title=Body of murder victim found in Gulmi |publisher=The Himalayan Times online |location=Gulmi |first=Hari |last=Sharma |date=2010-11-18 |accessdate=2011-05-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525142109/http://www.thehimalayantimes.com/fullNews.php?headline=Body+of+murder+victim+found+in+Gulmi&NewsID=266104 |archivedate=25 May 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"Hatlebakk07\">{{cite web|last=Hatlebakk |first=Magnus |year=2007 |title=Economic and social structures that may explain the recent conflicts in the Terai of Nepal |location=[[Kathmandu]] |publisher=Norwegian Embassy |url=http://www.norway.org.np/NR/rdonlyres/0993F5660B3548A98F819167B4FD596C/72944/http___wwwcmi.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=2011-05-08}}</ref>\n\nBahun and Chhetri castes form the historical topmost state elites' circle with the significant majority of leadership in executive, legislative, judicial, constitutional, local administrative bodies, [[bureaucracy]], [[political parties]] and social organizations. Hindu [[varna]] system highlights these castes as ''high castes'' and makes them favorable in higher social status due to favorable social norms, values, and laws.\n<ref>http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2016-04-05/caste-of-characters.html</ref>\n\n== List of ethnic groups in Nepal by population ==\nThe population wise ranking of 125 Nepalese castes/ethnic groups as per [[2011 Nepal census]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://nepal.unfpa.org/sites/default/files/pub-pdf/Population%20Monograph%20V02.pdf|title=Population Monograph of Nepal Volume II (Social Demography)}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://cbs.gov.np/image/data/Population/Population%20Monograph%20of%20Nepal%202014/Population%20Monograph%20V02.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-06-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170918043750/http://cbs.gov.np/image/data/Population/Population%20Monograph%20of%20Nepal%202014/Population%20Monograph%20V02.pdf |archive-date=2017-09-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{refn|group=note|Pages 191/192 of the total pdf or pages 156/157 in the scanned material shows Nepalese castes/ethnic groups}}<ref>{{Cite web|URL=https://unstats.un.org/unsD/demographic/sources/census/wphc/Nepal/Nepal-Census-2011-Vol1.pdf|title=Nepal Census 2011}}</ref>\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n!Rank\n! Caste/Ethnic groups \n!Broad Ethnic Category\n! Population (2011)\n! Percentage (%)\n|-\n|1\n| [[Chhetri|Kshetri/Chhetri]]\n|Khas\n| 4,398,053\n| 16.60%\n|-\n|2\n| [[Bahun|Brahmin-Hill/Bahun]]\n|Khas\n| 3,226,903\n| 12.18%\n|-\n|3\n| [[Magar people|Magar]]\n|Janajati-Hill\n| 1,887,733\n| 7.12%\n|-\n|4\n| [[Tharu people|Tharu]]\n|Adivasi-Tarai\n| 1,737,470\n| 6.56%\n|-\n|5\n| [[Tamang people|Tamang]]\n|Janajati-Hill\n| 1,539,830\n| 5.81%\n|-\n|6\n| [[Newar]] \n|Newar\n| 1,321,933\n| 4.99%\n|-\n|7\n| [[Kami (caste)|Kami]]\n|Khas (Dalit)\n| 1,258,554\n| 4.75%\n|-\n|8\n| [[Nepali Muslims|Musalman/Nepali Muslims]]\n|Muslim\n| 1,164,255\n| 4.39%\n|-\n|9\n|[[Yadav]]\n|Madhesi (Low)\n| 1,054,458\n| 3.98%\n|-\n|10\n| [[Rai (ethnic group)|Rai]]\n|Janajati-Hill\n| 620,004\n| 2.34%\n|-\n|11\n| [[Gurung people|Gurung]]\n|Janajati-Hill\n| 522,641\n|1.97%\n|-\n|12\n| [[Damai|Damai/Dholi]]\n|Khas (Dalit)\n|472,862\n|1.78%\n|-\n|13\n| [[Thakuri]]\n|Khas\n|425,623\n|1.61%\n|-\n|14\n| [[Limbu people|Limbu]]\n|Janajati-Hill\n|387,300\n|1.46%\n|-\n|15\n| [[Sarki (ethnic group)|Sarki]]\n|Khas (Dalit)\n|374,816\n|1.41%\n|-\n|16\n| [[Teli]]\n|Madhesi (Low)\n|369,688\n|1.40%\n|-\n|17\n| [[Chamar|Chamar/Harijan/Ram]]\n|Madhesi (Dalit)\n|335,893\n|1.27%\n|-\n|18\n|[[Kushwaha|Koiri/Kushwaha]]\n|Madhesi (Low)\n|306,393\n|1.16%\n|-\n|19\n| [[Musahar]]\n|Madhesi (Dalit)\n|234,490\n|0.89%\n|-\n|20\n|[[Kurmi]]\n|Madhesi (Low)\n|231,129\n|0.87%\n|-\n|21\n|[[Sanyasi|Sanyasi/Dasnami]]\n|Khas\n|227,822\n|0.86%\n|-\n|22\n|[[Dhanuk]]\n|Madhesi (Low)\n|219,808\n|0.83%\n|-\n|23\n|[[Kandu|Kanu/Haluwai]] \n|Madhesi (Low)\n|209,053\n|0.79%\n|-\n|24\n|[[Dusadh|Dusadh/Pasawan/Pasi]]\n|Madhesi (Dalit)\n|208,910\n|0.79%\n|-\n|25\n|[[Mallaha]]\n|Madhesi (Low)\n|173,261\n|0.65%\n|-\n|26\n|[[Kewat]]\n|Madhesi (Low)\n|153,772\n|0.58%\n|-\n|27\n|Kathabaniyan\n|Madhesi (Low)\n|138,637\n|0.52%\n|-\n|28\n| [[Brahmin]]-Tarai \n([[Maithil Brahmin|Maithil]], [[Kanyakubja Brahmin|Kanyakubja]], [[Bhumihar]])