am, Nepal\nFile:Gunla bajan performance.jpg|[[Newar]] group\nFile:Nepali Hindu Wedding (25).jpg|Procession of Khas Parbattia wedding\nFile:Sherpa.jpg|[[Sherpa people|Sherpa]], upper Tibetic ethnic group\nFile:Kirati Limbu women performing Kelang dance.jpg|Kirati Limbu women performing Kelang\nFile:Magar or Muggur, military tribe, Nipal.jpg|Magar man, military tribe, Nepal\nFile:Dashai.jpg|Senior offering ''Dashain Tika''; a feature of Khas Parbattia community\nFile:Drumming_Raute_elder.jpg|[[Raute people|Raute]] man; Rautes are below 1000\nFile:Magar group, military tribe, Nipal.jpg|Magar group, military tribe, Nepal\nFile:Kus or Khas, Goorkha, dominant tribe, Nipal.jpg|Khas man of Nepal, as depicted in ''The People of India'' (1868-1875)\nFile:Kurmi women in Hindustani dress 1916.jpg|[[Kurmi]] women\nFile:Magar woman dancing with traditional basket in Maghe Sakranti festival.jpg|Magar women\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Nepal}}\n{{Nepalese diaspora}}\n{{Asia in topic|Demographics of}}\n{{Asia topic|Ethnic groups in}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ethnic groups in Nepal}}\n[[Category:Demographics of Nepal| ]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Nepal]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=March 2018}}\n{{Pie chart\n|thumb = right\n|caption = Ethnic groups of Nepal (2011)<ref name=\"CIATONGA\">{{cite web|url= https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/np.html|title= South Asia ::NEPAL|publisher= CIA The World Factbook}}</ref>\n|label1 = [[Kshetri]]\n|value1 = 16.6\n|color1 = red\n|label2 = [[Brahman-Hill]]\n|value2 = 12.2\n|color2 = Orange\n|label3 = [[Magar people|Magar]]\n|value3 = 7.1\n|color3 = Green\n|label4 = [[Tharu people|Tharu]]\n|value4 = 6.6\n|color4 = Chartreuse\n|label5 = [[Tamang]]\n|value5 = 5.8\n|color5 = DodgerBlue\n|label6 = [[Newar]]\n|value6 = 5\n|color6 = HotPink\n|label7 = [[Kami (caste)|Kami]]\n|value7 = 4.8\n|color7 = Black\n|label8 = [[Nepalese Muslims]]\n|value8 = 4.4\n|color8 = silver\n|label9 = [[Yadav]]\n|value9 = 4\n|color9 = cyan\n|label10 = [[Rai (ethnic group)|Rai]]\n|value10 = 2.3\n|color10 = Yellow\n|label11 = Others\n|value11 = 31.2\n|color11 = skyblue\n}}\n[[File:Thapa boy.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Kshetri]], the largest caste group in Nepal]]\n\n[[File:Sakela_ladies.JPG|thumb| Rai ethnic group in Nepal]] \n[[File:Indigenous magar girls of Nepal.JPG|thumb|Indigenous [[Magars|Magar]] girls of Nepal; Magars are the largest [[Adivasi|Janjatis]] in Nepal]]\n[[File:JanakpurChhathParvaFestival.jpg|thumb|[[Madhesi people|Madheshis]] celebrating [[Chhath]] in Janakpur. Madheshis are a community of different caste groups of Terai in Nepal.]]\n\n'''Ethnic groups in Nepal''' are a product of both the colonial and state-building eras of [[Nepal]]. The groups are delineated using language, ethnic identity or the [[caste system in Nepal]]. They are categorized by common [[culture]] and [[endogamy]]. Endogamy carves out ethnic groups in Nepal.{{cn|date=April 2019}}\n\n==Linguistic groups==\n[[File:Dashain Tika 02.JPG|thumb|[[Khas people]] celebrating [[Dashain]] festival; Khas are the largest ethno-linguistic group in Nepal comprising [[Bahun]], [[Chhetri]], [[Kami (caste)|Kami]], [[Damai]] and other [[Dalit]]s]]\nNepal's diverse linguistic heritage evolved from three major language groups: [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan]], [[Tibeto-Burman languages]], and various [[indigenous language]] isolates. According to the 2001 national census, ninety two different living languages are spoken in Nepal (a ninety third category was \"unspecified\"). Based upon the 2011 census, the major languages spoken in Nepal are Nepali , Maithili and Bhojpuri.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cbs.gov.np/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/Summary-Nepali.pdf |format=PDF |title=Official Summary of Census |year=2011 |work=Central Bureau of Statistics, Nepal |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121202145804/http://cbs.gov.np/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/Summary-Nepali.pdf |archivedate=2 December 2012 }}</ref>\n\nSince Nepal's unification, various indigenous languages have come under threat of extinction as the government of Nepal has marginalized their use through strict policies designed to promote Nepali as the official language. Indigenous languages which have gone extinct or are critically threatened include Byangsi, Chonkha, and Longaba. Since democracy was restored in 1990, however, the government has worked to improve the marginalization of these languages. Tribhuvan University began surveying and recording threatened languages in 2010 and the government intends to use this information to include more languages on the next Nepalese census.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tumbahang|first=Govinda Bahadur|year=2010|title=Marginalization of indigenous languages of Nepal|url=|journal=Contributions to Nepalese Studies|volume=37|pages=69|via=Expanded Academic}}</ref>\n\n==Social status==\n[[File:SunuwarMaleFemale.jpg|thumbnail|[[Sunuwar]], a division of [[Kirati people]]; one of the largest ethnic cluster in Eastern Nepal]]\n[[Pahari people|Pahari]] Hill Hindus of the [[Khas|Khas Gorkha]] tribe ([[Bahun|Brahmin/Bahun]] and [[Chhetri]] castes) and the [[Newar people|Newar ethnicity]] dominated the civil service, the judiciary and upper ranks of the army throughout the [[Kingdom of Nepal|Shah regime]] (1768\u20132008). Nepali was the national language and [[Sanskrit]] became a required school subject. Children who spoke Nepali natively and who were exposed to Sanskrit had much better chances of passing the national examinations at the end of high school, which meant they had better employment prospects and could continue into higher education.\n\nOn the other hand, children who natively spoke local languages of the [[Madhesh]] and [[Hill Region|Hills]], or Tibetan dialects prevailing in the high mountains were at a considerable disadvantage. This history of exclusion coupled with poor prospects for improvement created grievances that encouraged many in ethnic communities such as [[Madhesi people|Madhesi]], [[Tharu people|Tharu]] and [[Kham Magar]] to support the [[Unified Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist)]] and various other armed Maoist opposition groups such as the [[JTMM]] during and after the [[Nepalese Civil War]]. The negotiated end to this war forced King [[Gyanendra of Nepal|Gyanendra]] to abdicate in 2008.\n\nIssues of ethnic and regional equity have tended to dominate the agenda of the new republican government and continue to be divisive. Today, even after the end of a 10-year-old Maoist conflict, the upper caste dominates every field in Nepal. Specifically, Brahmin and Chhetri (Indo-Aryan) have advantages. Although Newars are low in numbers, their urban living habitat gives them a competitive advantage. Thus, Newars are at the top of the Human Development Index. From a [[Gender inequality in Nepal|gender perspective]], Newari women are the most literate and lead in every sector. Brahmin and Chhetri women have experienced less social and economic mobility compared to Newari women. Specifically, Brahmin women experience less equality due to their predominately rural living conditions which deprives them of access to certain educational and healthcare benefits.<ref name=\"OCHA1\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.internal-displacement.org/8025708F004CE90B/(httpDocuments)/B66F206172F49BE4C12572D50030C3F0/$file/OCHA+overview+no+12+April+07.pdf |format=PDF |title=OCHA Nepal \u2013 Situation Overview |volume=Issue 12 |date=April 2007 |publisher=[[OCHA]] |accessdate=2011-05-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091113112940/http://www.internal-displacement.org/8025708F004CE90B/(httpDocuments)/B66F206172F49BE4C12572D50030C3F0/$file/OCHA+overview+no+12+April+07.pdf |archivedate=13 November 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"OCHA2\">{{cite journal|url=http://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/2E89F2121C2C57A24925733F000F4F21-Full_report.pdf |format=PDF |title=OCHA Nepal \u2013 Situation Overview |volume=Issue 16 |date=July\u2013August 2007 |publisher=[[OCHA]] |accessdate=2011-05-07}}</ref><ref name=\"OCHA3\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.internal-displacement.org/8025708F004CE90B/(httpDocuments)/5CC0BE0C971587F2C1257496004A9B9E/$file/ocha+sitrep+12+july08.pdf |format=PDF |title=OCHA Nepal \u2013 Situation Overview |volume=Issue 30 |date=June\u2013July 2008 |publisher=[[OCHA]] |accessdate=2011-05-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100218090410/http://www.internal-displacement.org/8025708F004CE90B/(httpDocuments)/5CC0BE0C971587F2C1257496004A9B9E/$file/ocha+sitrep+12+july08.pdf |archivedate=18 February 2010 }}</ref><ref name=\"Him-ext\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thehimalayantimes.com/fullNews.php?headline=Body+of+murder+victim+found+in+Gulmi&NewsID=266104 |title=Body of murder victim found in Gulmi |publisher=The Himalayan Times online |location=Gulmi |first=Hari |last=Sharma |date=2010-11-18 |accessdate=2011-05-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525142109/http://www.thehimalayantimes.com/fullNews.php?headline=Body+of+murder+victim+found+in+Gulmi&NewsID=266104 |archivedate=25 May 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"Hatlebakk07\">{{cite web|last=Hatlebakk |first=Magnus |year=2007 |title=Economic and social structures that may explain the recent conflicts in the Terai of Nepal |location=[[Kathmandu]] |publisher=Norwegian Embassy |url=http://www.norway.org.np/NR/rdonlyres/0993F5660B3548A98F819167B4FD596C/72944/http___wwwcmi.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=2011-05-08}}</ref>\n\nBahun and Chhetri castes form the historical topmost state elites' circle with the significant majority of leadership in executive, legislative, judicial, constitutional, local administrative bodies, [[bureaucracy]], [[political parties]] and social organizations. Hindu [[varna]] system highlights these castes as ''high castes'' and makes them favorable in higher social status due to favorable social norms, values, and laws.\n<ref>http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2016-04-05/caste-of-characters.html</ref>\n\n== List of ethnic groups in Nepal by population ==\nThe population wise ranking of 125 Nepalese castes/ethnic groups as per [[2011 Nepal census]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://nepal.unfpa.org/sites/default/files/pub-pdf/Population%20Monograph%20V02.pdf|title=Population Monograph of Nepal Volume II (Social Demography)}}</ref>.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://cbs.gov.np/image/data/Population/Population%20Monograph%20of%20Nepal%202014/Population%20Monograph%20V02.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-06-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170918043750/http://cbs.gov.np/image/data/Population/Population%20Monograph%20of%20Nepal%202014/Population%20Monograph%20V02.pdf |archive-date=2017-09-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{refn|group=note|Pages 191/192 of the total pdf or pages 156/157 in the scanned material shows Nepalese castes/ethnic groups}}<ref>{{Cite web|URL=https://unstats.un.org/unsD/demographic/sources/census/wphc/Nepal/Nepal-Census-2011-Vol1.pdf|title=Nepal Census 2011}}</ref>\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n!Rank\n! Caste/Ethnic groups \n!Broad Ethnic Category\n! Population (2011)\n! Percentage (%)\n|-\n|1\n| [[Chhetri|Kshetri/Chhetri]]\n|Khas\n| 4,398,053\n| 16.60%\n|-\n|2\n| [[Bahun|Brahmin-Hill/Bahun]]\n|Khas\n| 3,226,903\n| 12.18%\n|-\n|3\n| [[Magar people|Magar]]\n|Janajati-Hill\n| 1,887,733\n| 7.12%\n|-\n|4\n| [[Tharu people|Tharu]]\n|Adivasi-Tarai\n| 1,737,470\n| 6.56%\n|-\n|5\n| [[Tamang people|Tamang]]\n|Janajati-Hill\n| 1,539,830\n| 5.81%\n|-\n|6\n| [[Newar]] \n|Newar\n| 1,321,933\n| 4.99%\n|-\n|7\n| [[Kami (caste)|Kami]]\n|Khas (Dalit)\n| 1,258,554\n| 4.75%\n|-\n|8\n| [[Nepali Muslims|Musalman/Nepali Muslims]]\n|Muslim\n| 1,164,255\n| 4.39%\n|-\n|9\n|[[Yadav]]\n|Madhesi (Low)\n| 1,054,458\n| 3.98%\n|-\n|10\n| [[Rai (ethnic group)|Rai]]\n|Janajati-Hill\n| 620,004\n| 