{"title_page": "Ethiopian Athletics Federation", "text_new": "{{Infobox sport governing body|name=Ethiopian Athletics Federation|logo=Ethiopian_Athletics_Federation.jpg|logosize=|sport=[[Athletics (sport)|Athletics]]|abbrev=EAF|founded= 4 June 1961|aff=|location=[[Addis Ababa]], [[Ethiopia]]|affdate=|region=|regionyear=|president=[[Haile Gebrselassie]]|chairman=|secretary=|coach=|womenscoach=|replaced=|url=eaf.org.et}}\n\n'''Ethiopian Athletic Federation''' ('''EAF''') is an [[IAAF]] recognized member officially representing [[Ethiopia]] as the [[sports governing body|national governing body]] for the sport of [[Athletics (sport)|Athletics]].\n\n==History==\nThe history of the sport may be traced back to military and school organizations in 1897.  The organization was formed in 4 June 1961.<ref>https://eaf.org.et/aboout-eaf/history</ref> The ability of East African athletes was announced to the world in the [[Ethiopia at the 1960 Summer Olympics|1960 Olympics]] as barefooted [[Abebe Bikila]] took the gold medal in the [[Marathon]].  Bikila repeated in 1964 and the floodgates were opened.  Ethiopia has captured 45 Olympic medals, all of them in [[long distance running]] through 2012, despite participating in three Olympic boycotts.  The organization is also responsible for selecting representatives to other world championship events.\n\nIn November of 2016, former Olympic gold medalist and Ethiopian long distance running great [[Haile Gebrselassie]] was elected president of the Ethiopian Athletics Federation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-athletics-ethiopia-gebrselassie-idUSKBN1310PP|title=Athletics: Distance great Gebrselassie elected Ethiopia athletics chief|last=Maasho|first=Aaron|date=November 6, 2016|work=reuters|access-date=}}</ref> On November 14, 2018, Double Olympic champion, [[Derartu Tulu]] has succeeded Haile Gebrselassie as president of EAF.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aipsmedia.com/index.html?page=artdetail&oldart=23785|title=AIPS Media|website=www.aipsmedia.com|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> \n\n==Kit suppliers==\nEthiopia's kits are currently supplied by [[Adidas]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|1=http://eaf.org.et/}}\n\n{{Sports governing bodies in Ethiopia}}\n{{National Members of the International Association of Athletics Federations}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ethiopian Athletic Federation}}\n[[Category:National members of the Confederation of African Athletics]]\n[[Category:Athletics in Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Sports governing bodies in Ethiopia|Athletics]]\n[[Category:National governing bodies for athletics]]\n[[Category:Sports organizations established in 1961]]\n\n\n{{athletics-stub}}\n{{Ethiopia-sport-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sport governing body|name=Ethiopian Athletics Federation|logo=Ethiopian_Athletics_Federation.jpg|logosize=|sport=[[Athletics (sport)|Athletics]]|abbrev=EAF|founded= 4 June 1961|aff=|location=[[Addis Ababa]], [[Ethiopia]]|affdate=|region=|regionyear=|president=[[Haile Gebrselassie]]|chairman=|secretary=|coach=|womenscoach=|replaced=|url=eaf.org.et}}\n\n'''Ethiopian Athletic Federation''' ('''EAF''') is an [[IAAF]] recognized member officially representing [[Ethiopia]] as the [[sports governing body|national governing body]] for the sport of [[Athletics (sport)|Athletics]].\n\n==History==\nThe history of the sport may be traced back to military and school organizations in 1897.  The organization was formed in 4 June 1961.<ref>https://eaf.org.et/aboout-eaf/history</ref> The ability of East African athletes was announced to the world in the [[Ethiopia at the 1960 Summer Olympics|1960 Olympics]] as barefooted [[Abebe Bikila]] took the gold medal in the [[Marathon]].  Bikila repeated in 1964 and the floodgates were opened.  Ethiopia has captured 45 Olympic medals, all of them in [[long distance running]] through 2012, despite participating in three Olympic boycotts.  The organization is also responsible for selecting representatives to other world championship events.\n\nIn November of 2016, former Olympic gold medalist and Ethiopian long distance running great [[Haile Gebrselassie]] was elected president of the Ethiopian Athletics Federation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-athletics-ethiopia-gebrselassie-idUSKBN1310PP|title=Athletics: Distance great Gebrselassie elected Ethiopia athletics chief|last=Maasho|first=Aaron|date=November 6, 2016|work=reuters|access-date=}}</ref> On November 14, 2018, Double Olympic champion, [[Derartu Tulu]] has succeeded Haile Gebrselassie as president of EAF<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aipsmedia.com/index.html?page=artdetail&oldart=23785|title=AIPS Media|website=www.aipsmedia.com|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>. \n\n==Kit suppliers==\nEthiopia's kits are currently supplied by [[Adidas]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|1=http://eaf.org.et/}}\n\n{{Sports governing bodies in Ethiopia}}\n{{National Members of the International Association of Athletics Federations}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ethiopian Athletic Federation}}\n[[Category:National members of the Confederation of African Athletics]]\n[[Category:Athletics in Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Sports governing bodies in Ethiopia|Athletics]]\n[[Category:National governing bodies for athletics]]\n[[Category:Sports organizations established in 1961]]\n\n\n{{athletics-stub}}\n{{Ethiopia-sport-stub}}\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ethiopian_Athletics_Federation"}
{"title_page": "Estonian science fiction", "text_new": "'''Science fiction and fantasy in [[Estonia]]''' is largely a product of the current post-Soviet era. Although somewhat earlier authors, like [[Eiv Eloon]] and {{ill|Tiit Tarlap|et}}, do exist.<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=http://earlyelm.estinst.ee/issue/11/estonian-science-fiction/ |title = Estonian science-fiction | last = Sulbi | first = Raul | magazine = Estonian Literary Magazine}}</ref> \n\n[[:et:Eesti Ulme\u00fching|Eesti Ulme\u00fching]] is an organization for print science fiction in Estonia that awards annual Stalker prizes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ulme.ee/veeb/?page_id=3819&lang=en |title=Estonian Science Fiction Association's page on Stalker awards |access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref> The awards are named after the [[Andrei Tarkovsky]] film [[Stalker (1979 film)|Stalker]] that was largely shot in Estonia. \n\nIn film the works of Raul Tammet have been analyzed.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1386/seec.1.2.167_1 | volume=1 | title=Aliens and time travellers: Recycling national space in Estonian science-fiction cinema | year=2010 | journal=Studies in Eastern European Cinema | pages=167\u2013182 | last1 = N\u00e4ripea | first1 = Eva}}</ref>\n\n== A selection of Estonian writers who have won multiple Stalkers ==\n*{{ill|Veiko Belials|et}}\n*{{ill|Lew R. Berg|et}}\n*{{ill|Indrek Hargla|d|Q717697}} - Pen-name for Indrek Sootak, he also writes [[detective fiction]] that has been translated to English.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.peterowenpublishers.com/books/apothecary-melchior-mystery-st-olafs-church/ |title=Peter Owen Publishers |access-date=2015-10-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118000740/http://www.peterowenpublishers.com/books/apothecary-melchior-mystery-st-olafs-church/ |archive-date=2015-11-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*[[Leo Kunnas]]\n*{{ill|Tiit Tarlap|et}}\n*{{ill|Siim Veskimees|et}}\n\nThe novel ''[[The Man Who Spoke Snakish]]'' by [[Andrus Kivir\u00e4hk]] was awarded the Stalker award in 2008.<ref>[http://www.estlit.ee/elis/?cmd=writer&id=09854&txt=79858 Stalker Award for Science Fiction 2008]. Estonian Literature Centre.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Andrus Org]]. [https://dspace.ut.ee/handle/10062/55882 ''Eesti ulmekirjanduse \u017eanrid ja nende poeetika'']. (The Genre System of Estonian Fantastic Fiction and its Poetics, PhD thesis). Tartu: University of Tartu Press, 2017. (Dissertationes litterarum et contemplationis comparativae Universitatis Tartuensis 16.)\n* [[Andrus Org]]. The Dimensions of the Contemporary Science Fiction Novel on the Basis of Examples from Estonian Literature. \u2013 [http://dspace.ut.ee/handle/10062/54904?show=full ''Interlitteraria'' 2004, No 9], pp. 226\u2013237.\n* [[Andrus Org]]. [https://www.etis.ee/File/DownloadPublic/c4f74c05-1a58-4c9d-8b9e-db7cdda73937?name=pdf%20%28Org%29.pdf&type=application%2Fpdf Fantastic fiction in Estonian literature: fields of genres and their sources of influence.] In: Martin Carayol (Ed.). ''Le fantastique et la science-fiction en Finlande et en Estonie''. Paris: L'Harmattan, 2012, pp. 35\u201345. (Biblioth\u00e8que finno-ougrienne 23.)\n\n[[Category:Estonian science fiction|*]]\n{{Science fiction}}\n{{Estonia-stub}}\n{{sf-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Science fiction and fantasy in [[Estonia]]''' is largely a product of the current post-Soviet era. Although somewhat earlier authors, like [[Eiv Eloon]] and {{ill|Tiit Tarlap|et}}, do exist.<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=http://earlyelm.estinst.ee/issue/11/estonian-science-fiction/ |title = Estonian science-fiction | last = Sulbi | first = Raul | magazine = Estonian Literary Magazine}}</ref> \n\n[[:et:Eesti Ulme\u00fching|Eesti Ulme\u00fching]] is an organization for print science fiction in Estonia that awards annual Stalker prizes<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ulme.ee/veeb/?page_id=3819&lang=en |title=Estonian Science Fiction Association's page on Stalker awards |access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>. The awards are named after the [[Andrei Tarkovsky]] film [[Stalker (1979 film)|Stalker]] that was largely shot in Estonia. \n\nIn film the works of Raul Tammet have been analyzed.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1386/seec.1.2.167_1 | volume=1 | title=Aliens and time travellers: Recycling national space in Estonian science-fiction cinema | year=2010 | journal=Studies in Eastern European Cinema | pages=167\u2013182 | last1 = N\u00e4ripea | first1 = Eva}}</ref>\n\n== A selection of Estonian writers who have won multiple Stalkers ==\n*{{ill|Veiko Belials|et}}\n*{{ill|Lew R. Berg|et}}\n*{{ill|Indrek Hargla|d|Q717697}} - Pen-name for Indrek Sootak, he also writes [[detective fiction]] that has been translated to English.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.peterowenpublishers.com/books/apothecary-melchior-mystery-st-olafs-church/ |title=Peter Owen Publishers |access-date=2015-10-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118000740/http://www.peterowenpublishers.com/books/apothecary-melchior-mystery-st-olafs-church/ |archive-date=2015-11-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*[[Leo Kunnas]]\n*{{ill|Tiit Tarlap|et}}\n*{{ill|Siim Veskimees|et}}\n\nThe novel ''[[The Man Who Spoke Snakish]]'' by [[Andrus Kivir\u00e4hk]] was awarded the Stalker award in 2008.<ref>[http://www.estlit.ee/elis/?cmd=writer&id=09854&txt=79858 Stalker Award for Science Fiction 2008]. Estonian Literature Centre.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Andrus Org]]. [https://dspace.ut.ee/handle/10062/55882 ''Eesti ulmekirjanduse \u017eanrid ja nende poeetika'']. (The Genre System of Estonian Fantastic Fiction and its Poetics, PhD thesis). Tartu: University of Tartu Press, 2017. (Dissertationes litterarum et contemplationis comparativae Universitatis Tartuensis 16.)\n* [[Andrus Org]]. The Dimensions of the Contemporary Science Fiction Novel on the Basis of Examples from Estonian Literature. \u2013 [http://dspace.ut.ee/handle/10062/54904?show=full ''Interlitteraria'' 2004, No 9], pp. 226\u2013237.\n* 